aller)|Martin Hayes]]|other=on loan from [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=POL|pos=MF|name=[[Zbigniew Kruszy\u0144ski]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=IRE|pos=MF|name=[[Paul McGee (footballer, born 1968)|Paul McGee]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Paul Miller (footballer, born 1968)|Paul Miller]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Vaughan Ryan]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=NIR|pos=MF|name=[[Lawrie Sanchez]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Steve Talboys]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Steve Anthrobus]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Andy Clarke]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Alan Cork]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Steve Cotterill]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[John Fashanu]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Terry Gibson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=-|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Aidan Newhouse]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Transfers==\n\n===In===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Pos\n!Name\n!From\n!Fee\n|-\n|19 July 1991\n|MF\n|[[Robbie Earle]]\n|[[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]\n|\u00a3775,000\n|-\n|10 January 1992\n|MF\n|[[Steve Talboys]]\n|[[Gloucester City A.F.C.|Gloucester City]]\n|\u00a310,000\n|}\n\n===Out===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Pos\n!Name\n!To\n!Fee\n|-\n|14 August 1991\n|DF\n|[[Keith Curle]]\n|[[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|\u00a32,500,000\n|}\n\n:Transfers in: {{loss}} \u00a3785,000\n:Transfers out: {{gain}} \u00a32,500,000\n:Total spending: {{gain}} \u00a31,715,000\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wimbledon F.C.}}\n{{Wimbledon F.C. seasons}}\n{{1991\u201392 in English football}}\n\n[[Category:Wimbledon F.C. seasons|1991-92]]\n[[Category:1991\u201392 Football League First Division by team|Wimbledon]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - fix links -Andy Clarke", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1991%E2%80%9392_Wimbledon_F.C._season"}
{"title_page": "1990\u201391 in English football", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox football country season\n| country     = England\n| season      = 1990\u201391\n| division1   = [[1990\u201391 Football League First Division|First Division]]\n| champions1  = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| division2   = [[1990\u201391 Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n| champions2  = [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]]\n| division3   = [[1990\u201391 Football League Third Division|Third Division]]\n| champions3  = [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]\n| division4   = [[1990\u201391 Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]]\n| champions4  = [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]]\n| division5   = [[1990\u201391 Football Conference|Football Conference]]\n| champions5  = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n| domestic    = [[1990\u201391 FA Cup|FA Cup]]\n| dchampions  = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| domestic2   = [[1990\u201391 Associate Members' Cup|Associate Members' Cup]]\n| dchampions2 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n| leaguecup   = [[1990\u201391 Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n| lchampions  = [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]\n| supercup    = [[1990 FA Charity Shield|Charity Shield]]\n| schampions  = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] & [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| prevseason  = 1989\u201390\n| nextseason  = 1991\u201392\n| flagicon    = yes\n}}\nThe '''1990\u201391''' season was the 111th season of competitive [[football (soccer)|football]] in England.\n\n==Diary of the season==\n\n2 July 1990 - [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] prepare for their First Division comeback by signing midfielder [[Gary McAllister]] from [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] for \u00a31million.\n\n3 July 1990 - [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] pay a club record \u00a31.6million for [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] winger [[Dennis Wise]].\n\n4 July 1990 - [[England national football team|England's]] World Cup hopes are ended in a semi-final defeat by [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]], with [[Chris Waddle]] and [[Stuart Pearce]] both missing penalties.\n\n5 July 1990 - Chelsea sign [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] midfielder [[Andy Townsend]] for \u00a31.2million.\n\n16 July 1990 - [[Graham Taylor]], manager of [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], is appointed as successor to [[Bobby Robson]] as the England manager.\n\n18 July 1990 - [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] sign defender [[Paul Blades]] from Norwich City for \u00a3700,000.\n\n19 July 1990 - England striker [[Mark Hateley]] ends six years overseas and joins Scottish league champions [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in a \u00a31million move from [[AS Monaco]]. He had played on the continent since his move from [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] to [[AC Milan]] in 1984.\n\n20 July 1990 \u2013 Manchester City pay a club record \u00a31 million for [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] goalkeeper [[Tony Coton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=1718&comp_id=1&teamTabs=transfers|title=Latest Man City Transfers - Full Transfer History - Soccer Base|author=|date=|website=www.soccerbase.com|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n22 July 1990 - [[Czechoslovakia|Czech]] national coach [[Jozef Venglos]] is appointed as the new manager of Aston Villa, and becomes the first foreign manager in the First Division.\n\n31 July 1990 - [[Aldershot F.C.]] in the Fourth Division are wound up in the High Court, condemned as \"hopelessly insolvent\" with debts of nearly \u00a3500,000 by the Official Receiver.\n\n1 August 1990 \u2013\n\n* - The [[Football League]] confirms that it will revert to a 22-club First Division for the [[1991\u201392 in English football|1991\u201392 season]], while total league membership will be increased to 94 clubs for the 1992\u201393 season, with the Second, Third and Fourth Divisions each having 24 clubs.\n* - [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] sell striker [[Dalian Atkinson]] to [[Real Sociedad]] of [[Spain]] for \u00a31million, where he will be playing alongside the former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] striker [[John Aldridge]]. Long-serving [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] defender [[Mike Duxbury]] joins [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on a free transfer.\n\n6 August 1990 - [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] sign [[Sweden|Swedish]] winger [[Anders Limpar]] from Italian side [[Cremonese]] for \u00a31million.\n\n7 August 1990 \u2013 Aldershot are saved from closure by a \u00a3200,000 rescue package put together by 19-year-old property developer [[Spencer Trethewy]], which means that they will be able to start the new Football League season.<ref name=\"mirrorfootball.co.uk\">[http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/blogs/mirror-football-blog/Newcastle-s-Freddy-Shepherd-Chelsea-s-Ken-Bates-Leeds-Peter-Ridsdale-Palace-s-Simon-Jordan-and-the-Top-10-crazy-football-chairman-article320687.html Newcastle's Freddy Shepherd, Chelsea's Ken Bates, Leeds' Peter Ridsdale, Palace's Simon Jordan and the Top 10 crazy football chairman \u2013 Mirror Football Blog]. MirrorFootball.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n15 August 1990 - [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] sign [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] defender [[Eric Young (footballer, born 1960)|Eric Young]] for \u00a3850,000.\n\n16 August 1990 - Crystal Palace further strengthen their defence with a \u00a3400,000 move for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], their [[Selhurst Park]] tenants, for [[John Humphrey (footballer)|John Humphrey]].\n\n18 August 1990 \u2013 Liverpool and Manchester United share the [[1990 FA Charity Shield|Charity Shield]] after a 1\u20131 draw at Wembley.\n\n23 August 1990 \u2013 [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] pay a club record \u00a3460,000 for [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] striker [[David Currie (footballer)|David Currie]]. [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] are warned that they face expulsion from the Football League if measures aimed by the Football Association at curbing incidents of hooliganism involving the club's fans fail.<ref>[http://www.newsint-archive.co.uk/pages/S.asp?pubsel=BOTH&SrchText=football+and+hooligans&DateFromDD=01&DateFromMM=Aug&DateFromYY=1990&DateToDD=31&DateToMM=Jul&DateToYY=1991&ResultListMax=200&head=&byline=&sect=&Caption=&edn=&page=&SortOrder=Asc&SortField=SDate&Submit1=Search&BackDD=Day&BackMM=Month&BackYY=Year&source=thetimes&SortField=Pub&SortOrder=asc&SortField=EDN&SortOrder=asc&SortField=Page&SortOrder=asc&ST=NS&SortSpec=&ResultMaxDocs=200&Site=ALL&Collection=NI&ResultCount=20&summreqd=yes&indexkey=31C3128516001143593E190&advsrch=0&QueryText=%28football+and+hooligans%29+%3CAND%3E+%28PUB%3DBOTH%29+%3CAND%3E+%28%28SDate%3E%3D8%2F1%2F1990%29+%3CAND%3E+%28SDate%3C%3D7%2F31%2F1991%29%29&_P=1 The Times and The Sunday Times Archive]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Newsint-archive.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n24 August 1990 - [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] sign midfielder [[Mike Milligan (footballer)|Mike Milligan]] from [[Oldham Athletic]] for \u00a31million.\n\n25 August 1990 \u2013 Liverpool begin their defence of the First Division title with a 3\u20131 away win against recently promoted [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\">{{cite book|last=Smailes|first=Gordon|title=The Breedon Book of Football Records|year=2000|publisher=Breedon Books|location=Derby|isbn=1859832148|pages=166}}</ref>[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] begin their challenge for a second league title in three seasons by beating [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] 3-0 at [[Plough Lane]]. [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] enjoy a fine First Division comeback with a 3-2 away win over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. Key games on the opening day of the Second Division campaign include a 4-2 home win over [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] for newly promoted [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] and [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United's]] 5-2 home win over [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]. In the Fourth Division, [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] draw 2-2 with [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]] in their first game at the new [[Bescot Stadium]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-08-25.html]</ref>\n\n28 August 1990 - [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and Leeds United meet for the first time since April 1982, and battle out a goalless draw at [[Elland Road]] in the First Division - a repeat of the last clash between the two sides.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-08-28.html]</ref>\n\n31 August 1990 \u2013 The first month of the English league season ends with Arsenal and Liverpool sharing the lead in the First Division after two games.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> The Second Division leaders are Oldham Athletic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics MAD |author=Entertainment & Sports Agency Limited |url=http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=28&Month=Aug&ssnno=120&teamno=404 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007113745/http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=28&Month=Aug&ssnno=120&teamno=404 |archivedate=2011-10-07 |url-status=live |accessdate=2009-05-17 }}</ref>\n\n1 September 1990 \u2013 Newly promoted First Division side [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] achieve a shock 2\u20131 league win over FA Cup holders Manchester United at [[Roker Park]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Liverpool's 3-1 home win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] leaves them with the only 100% record in the First Division after three games. Leeds go second with a 3-0 home win over [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]. Everton's 1-0 defeat to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] at [[Maine Road]] leaves with without a point from their opening three games. There are victories in the Second Division for promotion favourites [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-01.html]</ref>\n\n4 September 1990 - The only league action of the day sees a [[Mark Robins]] goal give Manchester United a 1-0 away win over [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-04.html]</ref>\n\n8 September 1990 - Liverpool extend their winning start to the season to four games with a 2-1 away win over Wimbledon. Mark Robins is the star of the show for Manchester United once again, scoring twice in a 3-1 home win over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]]. [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] go second with a 3-0 win at Norwich. [[Paul Gascoigne]] scores a hat-trick for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] in their 3-0 home win over [[Derby County F.C.|Derby]]. Everton claim their first point of the season with a 1-1 draw at home to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Oldham have a 100% record after four games, remaining top of the Second Division with a 1-0 win at [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-08.html]</ref>\n\n10 September 1990 - Manager [[Joe Jordan]] leaves Bristol City to return to his native [[Scotland]] and become manager of [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]].\n\n12 September 1990 \u2013 England beat [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] 1\u20130 in a friendly at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]], the first game under Graham Taylor's management. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n15 September 1990 - Arsenal keep up the pressure on Liverpool with a 4-1 home win over Chelsea, as do Tottenham with a 2-0 win at Leeds. Oldham make it five wins in a row in the Second Division by beating Oxford 3-0 at [[Boundary Park]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-15.html]</ref>\n\n16 September 1990 \u2013 [[Peter Beardsley]] scores a hat-trick for Liverpool in their 4\u20130 league win over Manchester United at [[Anfield]].<ref>[http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/history/past-players/peter-beardsley Peter Beardsley \u2013 Liverpool FC]. Liverpoolfc.tv. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n18 September 1990 - Oldham drop points for the first time this season with a 1-1 draw at home to Charlton, who claim their first point of the season in the process.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-18.html]</ref>\n\n22 September 1990 - Liverpool extend their winning start to the season to six games by winning the [[Merseyside derby]] 3-2 at [[Goodison Park]]. Arsenal keep up the pressure and hold onto second place with a 2-0 win at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]. Oldham remain top of the Second Division with a 1-0 win over [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] at [[Ayresome Park]]. [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] draw level with the top three by beating local rivals Oxford 4-2 at the [[Manor Ground (Oxford)|Manor Ground]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-22.html]</ref>\n\n25 September 1990 \u2013 [[Ian Wright]] and [[Mark Bright]] both score hat-tricks for Crystal Palace in their 8\u20130 home win over Southend United in the League Cup second round first leg at [[Selhurst Park]].<ref>[http://www.holmesdale.net/page.php?id=82&story=4702 Top 10 hat-tricks \u2013 Crystal Palace FC Supporters' Website \u2013 The Holmesdale Online]. Holmesdale.net. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n26 September 1990 \u2013 Paul Gascoigne scores four goals for Tottenham in their 5\u20130 win over Hartlepool United (managed by former Tottenham defender [[Cyril Knowles]]) in the League Cup second round first leg at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref>[http://www.topspurs.com/9091.htm the world famous unofficial home of Spurs on the internet]. Topspurs. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n29 September 1990 - Liverpool's 1-0 win over Sunderland at [[Roker Park]] gives them a 100% record after seven games, and they extend their lead to six points after Arsenal are held to a 2-2 draw at Leeds. Tottenham and Crystal Palace are level on points with [[George Graham (footballer)|George Graham]]'s men. Manchester United's title hopes are dented when a [[Stuart Pearce]] goal gives Nottingham Forest a 1-0 win at [[Old Trafford]]. Luton climb to sixth place with a 3-1 win over Norwich at [[Carrow Road]]. Sheffield United and Derby occupy the bottom places, both winless after seven games. Oldham remain top of the Second Division despite being held to a goalless draw at [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-29.html]</ref>\n\n30 September 1990 \u2013 Liverpool, with a 100% record after seven games, are First Division leaders by six points at the end of September. The bottom two places are occupied by Sheffield United and Derby County, who have both yet to win a league game this season.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> In the Second Division, Oldham Athletic lead the way with 20 points from their opening eight games. The other two automatic promotion places are occupied by [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], and the playoff zone is occupied by [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] (in contention for a second successive promotion), [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] and [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]].<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=29&Month=Sep&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1990-09-29). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 October 1990 - [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] go second in the Second Division with a 1-0 win at Port Vale, boosting their hopes of a second successive promotion.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-01.html]</ref>\n\n4 October 1990 \u2013 [[Peter Thomas Taylor|Peter Taylor]], former managerial partner of [[Brian Clough]], dies suddenly of pulmonary fibrosis whilst on holiday in Costa De Los Pinos, Majorca, at the age of 62.\n\n6 October 1990 \u2013 In the biggest Second Division win of the season, [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] beat [[Hull City F.C.|Hull City]] 7\u20131 at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]].<ref>[http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=4&ham=1991&united=2nd_Division_1990-91 2nd Division 1990\u201391]. Westhamstats.info. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]] boost their hopes of a third promotion in four seasons by beating Bristol City 4-0 at home, with [[Steve Bull]] scoring a hat-trick. In the First Division, [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] draw 3-3 in a thrilling match at [[The Dell, Southampton|The Dell]]. Liverpool make it eight wins in a row by beating Derby 2-0 at [[Anfield]], while Arsenal keep the gap between themselves and the leaders at six points by beating Norwich 2-0 at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-06.html]</ref>\n\n7 October 1990 - The pressure mounts on Everton manager [[Colin Harvey]] after a 3-1 defeat at Nottingham Forest leaves his side third from bottom in the First Division after just one win and five points from their opening eight games.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-07.html]</ref>\n\n12 October 1990 \u2013 West Ham United strengthen their promotion bid with a \u00a3600,000 move for [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] defender [[Tim Breacker]].<ref name=\"soccerbase1\">[http://www.soccerbase.com/transfers_by_value.sd?lower_value=&higher_value=100000000&seasonid=120&x=31&y=4  Soccerbase] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n20 October 1990 \u2013 21 of the 22 players on the pitch [[Manchester United F.C.\u2013Arsenal F.C. brawl (1990)|brawl]] in Arsenal's 1\u20130 league win over Manchester United at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/5224475/Manchester-United-v-Arsenal-A-history-of-football-warfare.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Emma |last=Barrow |title=Manchester United v Arsenal: A history of football warfare |date=28 April 2009 |accessdate=30 October 2010  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929043529/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/5224475/Manchester-United-v-Arsenal-A-history-of-football-warfare.html |archivedate=29 September 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In their ninth league game of the season, Liverpool drop points for the first time when Norwich City hold them to a 1\u20131 draw at [[Carrow Road]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> The gap between first and second place is cut to four points as a result. Tottenham keep up the pressure with a 4-0 home win over Sheffield United, with [[Paul Walsh]] scoring a hat-trick. The bottom two clubs are still winless after nine games.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-20.html]</ref>\n\n24 October 1990 - Aston Villa beat Italian favourites [[Inter Milan]] 2-0 at [[Villa Park]] in the [[UEFA Cup]] second round first leg. In the Second Division, Newcastle's promotion hopes are hit by a 3-1 home defeat to struggling Charlton.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-24.html]</ref>\n\n27 October 1990 \u2013 The [[Manchester derby]] at [[Maine Road]] ends in a 3\u20133 draw between City and United.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Liverpool return to their winning ways with a 2-0 home win over Chelsea. Arsenal keep up the pressure with a 1-0 home win over Sunderland at Highbury, as do Tottenham with a 2-1 win at Nottingham Forest, and Crystal Palace with a thrilling 4-3 home win over Wimbledon. The top four in the First Division are all unbeaten after 10 games, as are the Second Division's top two clubs Oldham and West Ham after 14 games, and Fourth Division leaders Torquay after 13 games.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-27.html]</ref>\n\n31 October 1990 \u2013 [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] sack manager [[Colin Harvey]] after their worst start to a league season leaves them third from bottom in the First Division. Below them are Derby County and winless Sheffield United, while Liverpool remain top with nine wins from their opening 10 games. Arsenal, Tottenham Hotspur and Crystal Palace are their nearest contenders, and the top four are all still undefeated in the league.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> The Second Division promotion race is heating up, with Oldham Athletic still top of the table and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] having crept up to second place. Sheffield Wednesday occupy the third and final automatic promotion place. [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] have all climbed into the relegation zone this month. [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic's]] hopes of an immediate return to the First Division appear to be over as they occupy second from bottom place in the Second Division with eight defeats from their opening 13 games.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=27&Month=Oct&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1990-10-27). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref> The [[Football League Cup]] third round action includes a [[Mick Harford]] hat-trick for Derby in a 6-0 home win over his old club Sunderland. Manchester United beat Liverpool 3-1 at [[Old Trafford]]. Nottingham Forest keep their hopes of a third successive League Cup triumph alive with a 2-1 win at [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-31.html]</ref>\n\n1 November 1990 \u2013 Spencer Trethewy is dismissed from the Aldershot board of directors just three months after saving the club from closure, after it is revealed that he was unable to pay back the \u00a3200,000 he borrowed to keep the [[Hampshire]] based club afloat.<ref name=\"mirrorfootball.co.uk\"/>\n\n3 November 1990 - Crystal Palace suffer their first league defeat of the season when they lose 2-0 to Manchester United at Old Trafford. Derby beat Luton 2-1 to make it back-to-back victories in a boost to their survival hopes. Managerless Everton beat QPR 3-0 at Goodison Park.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-03.html]</ref>\n\n4 November 1990 - Tottenham's unbeaten league start ends and their title hopes are hit by a major blow when they lose 3-1 at home to Liverpool, who maintain a four-point lead over their nearest challengers Arsenal, while third placed Tottenham are now nine points off the top.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-04.html]</ref>\n\n7 November 1990 \u2013 [[Howard Kendall]] leaves [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] to begin his second spell as Everton manager.<ref>[http://www.evertonfc.com/history/howard-kendall.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6JFad8Drn?url=http://www.evertonfc.com/history/howard-kendall.html |date=30 August 2013 }} Evertonfc.com</ref> 34-year-old midfielder [[Peter Reid]] is put in temporary charge of Manchester City. Aston Villa's UEFA Cup hopes are ended when Inter Milan overturn a 2-0 Villa lead in the UEFA Cup second round second leg and win 3-0 in the [[San Siro]]. Manchester United go through to the quarter-finals of the European Cup Winners' Cup by completing a 5-0 aggregate win over [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-07.html]</ref>\n\n10 November 1990 - Liverpool extend their lead at the top of the First Division to six points with a 4-0 home win over Luton, while Arsenal can only manage a goalless draw with Crystal Palace at [[Selhurst Park]]. Tottenham keep their title hopes alive with a 4-2 home win over Wimbledon. Howard Kendall's return to Everton begins with a goalless draw against Sheffield United at [[Bramall Lane]], which keeps Everton in 17th place and means that their hosts are still bottom of the table and winless after 12 games. Derby hold Manchester United to a goalless draw at the [[Baseball Ground]] but miss the chance to climb out of the relegation zone.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-10.html]</ref>\n\n11 November 1990 - Leeds go fifth in the First Division with a 3-2 away win over Manchester City.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-11.html]</ref>\n\n12 November 1990 \u2013 Arsenal are deducted two points and Manchester United lose one point as punishment for last month's player brawl, which increases Liverpool's lead at the top to eight points.\n\n14 November 1990 - [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], 14th in the First Division and on course for their lowest league finish in five years, sack manager [[John Sillett]] after more than four years in charge. The only major action of the day is a 1-1 draw between England and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] in a Euro 92 qualifier at [[Lansdowne Road]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-14.html]</ref>\n\n15 November 1990 - [[Peter Reid]] is appointed player-manager of Manchester City. [[Terry Butcher]] returns to England after more than four years with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] to become player-manager at Coventry City. 31-year-old Butcher, who was released from his Rangers contract for a fee of \u00a3350,000, is the youngest manager in all four divisions of the English league.\n\n17 November 1990 - The first round of the [[FA Cup]] is contested. [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] and [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] are all eliminated by non-league opposition. In the First Division, Terry Butcher begins his managerial career with a 1-0 defeat at home to Liverpool, while second placed Arsenal beat Southampton 4-0. Sheffield United remain winless and bottom of the table after losing 2-0 to Manchester United at Old Trafford.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-17.html]</ref>\n\n21 November 1990 - Cardiff become the fourth league side to be knocked out of the FA Cup by non-league opposition when they lose their first round replay 1-0 to [[Isthmian League|Vauxhall-Opel League]] side [[Hayes F.C.|Hayes]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-21.html]</ref>\n\n27 November 1990 - Liverpool sign 19-year-old midfielder [[Don Hutchison]] from Fourth Division [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] for \u00a3175,000. Second Division bottom club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] sack manager [[Colin Lee]] after eight months in charge.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/walsall/1779667.stm]</ref>\n\n28 November 1990 - [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] beat [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 6-2 at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] in a League Cup fourth round tie, in which 19-year-old winger [[Lee Sharpe]] scores a hat-trick. Nottingham Forest's hopes of three League Cup triumphs in a row are ended when they lose 5-4 to Coventry at [[Highfield Road]], with [[Kevin Gallacher]] scoring a hat-trick for the winners and [[Nigel Clough]] scoring a hat-trick for the losers.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-28.html]</ref>\n\n29 November 1990 - Manchester United offer a professional contract to trainee winger [[Ryan Giggs]] on his 17th birthday.\n\n30 November 1990 \u2013 Liverpool remain unbeaten and top of the First Division as November draws to a close, four points ahead of an Arsenal side who are also unbeaten. Sheffield United are still looking for their first league win of the season after 14 games, while Derby County have climbed out of the relegation zone at the expense of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> In the Second Division, West Ham United have taken over from Oldham Athletic as Second Division leaders, while Sheffield Wednesday occupy third place. The playoff zone is occupied by Middlesbrough, Wolverhampton Wanderers, Millwall and Notts County. Newly promoted [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] stand just two points outside the playoff zone in 10th place, sparking hopes that manager [[Gerry Francis]] could soon deliver First Division football to the club for the first time ever.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=24&Month=Nov&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1990-11-24). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 December 1990 - Sheffield United are still looking for a league win 15 games into the season, with just four points to their name, after losing 2-1 at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], while Derby's upswing continues and they climb to 14th place with a 2-1 win at Sunderland, who stand 16th. A [[Lee Sharpe]] goal gives Manchester United a 1-0 win at Everton, United's first win at Goodison Park since January 1982. There is thrilling action in the Second Division when a 5-4 win for the hosts at [[Filbert Street]] sees [[David Kelly (association footballer)|David Kelly]] score a hat-trick for [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester]] and [[Micky Quinn]] score a hat-trick for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]]. The result helps lift Leicester clear of the relegation zone, while Newcastle are now 16th in the Second Division and six points adrift of the players, mounting the pressure on manager [[Jim Smith (footballer, born 1940)|Jim Smith]] who had almost delivered Newcastle promotion last season. West Ham remain top of the Second Division with a 3-1 home win over West Bromwich Albion, Port Vale close in on the playoffs with a 5-1 home win over Plymouth, Oldham retain second place with a 6-1 home win over Brighton, and Middlesbrough go third win a 3-0 home win over Hull.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-01.html]</ref>\n\n2 December 1990 \u2013 Arsenal end Liverpool's unbeaten League run by beating them 3\u20130 at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]], cutting the gap at the top to two points.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/>\n\n4 December 1990 \u2013 Luton Town win the [[Soccer Six]] at the [[Manchester Central Convention Complex|G-Mex Centre]], beating Liverpool 4\u20130 in the final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Six of the best from slick Luton|date=5 December 1990|url=http://kjellhanssen.com/1990/12/05/six-of-the-best-from-slick-luton/|accessdate=21 June 2015|work=Daily Express}}</ref>\n\n8 December 1990 - Heavy snow causes many Football League and FA Cup fixtures to be postponed, but a decent amount of matches in the less seriously affected areas go ahead. Arsenal miss the chance to go ahead at the top of the table on goal difference when they are held to a 1-1 draw at Luton. Tottenham draw 3-3 at home to Sunderland. The first match between Manchester United and Leeds United at Old Trafford for nearly a decade ends in a 1-1 draw. Everton increase Coventry's relegation worries and boost their own chances of staying clear of relegation with a 1-0 win at Goodison Park. West Ham remain firmly in the lead at the top of the Second Division with a 1-0 win at struggling Portsmouth.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-08.html]</ref>\n\n13 December 1990 \u2013 [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] pay \u00a31million for a player for the first time in their history by signing midfielder [[Alan McLoughlin]] from [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref name=\"Soccer Base\">[http://www.soccerbase.com/transfers_by_value.sd?lower_value=&higher_value=100000000&seasonid=120&x=31&y=4  Soccer Base] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n15 December 1990 - Liverpool are four points ahead at the top of the First Division, with a game in hand, after beating Sheffield United 2-0 to leave their hosts winless and still with only four points to their name so far this season, while Arsenal are held to a 2-2 draw at home to Wimbledon. A 10-goal thriller at the [[Baseball Ground]] sees Chelsea beat Derby 6-4. QPR remain second from bottom with a 2-1 defeat at home to Nottingham Forest.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-15.html]</ref>\n\n19 December 1990 - [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] captain [[Tony Adams]] is sentenced to four months in prison for drink-driving after being more than three times over the legal alcohol limit when he crashed his car in [[Southend-on-Sea]] seven months ago.\n\n21 December 1990 - Oldham go top of the Second Division on goal difference with a 5-3 home win over Plymouth.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-21.html]</ref>\n\n22 December 1990 \u2013 Sheffield United beat [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] to win their first First Division game of the season at the seventeenth attempt, but remain bottom of the table.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Liverpool remain comfortably in the lead at the top of the table with a 3-2 home win over Southampton. Manchester United win 3-1 at Wimbledon. West Ham miss out on the chance to return to the top of the Second Division with a 1-0 defeat at Barnsley.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-22.html]</ref>\n\n23 December 1990 - The last matches before Christmas are played. Arsenal extend their unbeaten start to the season to 18 games with a goalless draw at Aston Villa, although Liverpool are still six points ahead of them and have a game in hand. QPR miss the chance to climb out of the relegation zone when Derby hold them to a 1-1 draw at the Baseball Ground. Leeds hold on to fifth place with a 1-0 win over Sunderland at [[Roker Park]]. Three players are sent off in a goalless draw between Leicester and Watford at [[Filbert Street]]. In the Third Division, [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] boost their hopes of winning promotion in [[Phil Holder|Phil Holder's]] first season in management by beating [[Wigan Athletic]] 1-0 at [[Griffin Park]]. In the Fourth Division, [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] keep their playoff hopes alive with a 1-0 win over [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], who are now 18th in the table.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-23.html]</ref>\n\n26 December 1990 - The [[Boxing Day]] action in the First Division sees leaders Liverpool held to a 1-1 draw by QPR at [[Loftus Road]], allowing Arsenal to cut their lead to four points (with a game in hand) by beating Derby 3-0 at Highbury. Coventry boost their survival bid with a 2-0 home win over Tottenham. Crystal Palace remain in the hunt for the title with a 2-1 home win over Sunderland. Leeds go fourth with a 4-1 home win over Chelsea. Sheffield United make it back-to-back victories by winning 1-0 at Luton. Manchester United beat Norwich City 3-0 at [[Old Trafford]], ending [[Dave Stringer|Dave Stringer's]] team's run of five victories in their previous clashes between the two sides. West Ham go back to the top of the Second Division with a 2-0 home win over Oldham. Bristol City beat Portsmouth 4-1 to move to the brink of the playoff zone and boost their chances of a second successive promotion, while the bottom two of Hull and Oxford draw 3-3 at [[Boothferry Park]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-26.html]</ref>\n\n29 December 1990 - Arsenal cut Liverpool's lead of the First Division to a single point by beating Sheffield United 4-1 at Highbury, although [[Kenny Dalglish|Kenny Dalglish's]] men still have two games in hand. Leeds go third with a 3-0 home win over Wimbledon. Coventry, Everton, QPR and Southampton all claim victories in their fight to avoid relegation. There is no shortage of excitement in the Second Division, including Oxford climbing five places off the bottom of the table with a 3-1 win over Blackburn at [[Ewood Park]]. Ipswich and Charlton draw 4-4 at [[Portman Road]]. Newcastle's frustrating season continues with a 2-0 home defeat to Notts County, which leaves them rooted in the bottom half of the table.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-29.html]</ref>\n\n30 December 1990 - The last fixture of 1990 sees Liverpool lose 1-0 to Crystal Palace at Selhurst Park, which boosts [[Steve Coppell|Steve Coppell's]] side's hopes of winning their first ever major trophy in the shape of the league title.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-30.html]</ref>\n\n31 December 1990 \u2013 The year ends with Arsenal, still unbeaten but having had two points deducted, one point behind of Liverpool at the top of the First Division. Crystal Palace and Leeds United occupy third and fourth respectively, while Sheffield United remain bottom of the table and Sunderland have slipped into the bottom two.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> West Ham United stand top of the Second Division, followed in second place by Oldham Athletic and in third place by Sheffield Wednesday. Middlesbrough, Notts County, Wolverhampton Wanderers and Bristol City occupy the playoff zone. Newcastle United, who began the season among the favourites for promotion, occupy a lowly 16th place and are just four points above the relegation zone that threatens them with Third Division football for the first time.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=29&Month=Dec&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1990-12-29). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 January 1991 - The new year begins with [[Paul Gascoigne]] being sent off in Tottenham's 2-1 defeat at home to Manchester United. Everton's resurgence under Howard Kendall continues with a 2-1 win at Chelsea. Sheffield United make it three wins from four games but remain bottom of the table with a 1-0 home win over QPR. The biggest drama in the Second Division comes at [[Fratton Park]], where Portsmouth boost their survival hopes with a 5-1 home win over bottom club Hull City.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-01.html]</ref>\n\n2 January 1991 - Nottingham Forest beat Norwich 6-2 at [[Carrow Road]] in the First Division.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-02.html]</ref>\n\n5 January 1991 - The [[FA Cup]] third round produces a series of thrilling matches, perhaps the most notable being Second Division West Bromwich Albion's 4-2 home defeat to non-league [[Woking F.C.|Woking]]. [[National League|GM Vauxhall Conference]] title hopefuls [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] find themselves on the receiving end of a 5-0 defeat at home to Portsmouth. Chelsea suffer a shock 3-1 defeat at home to Second Division strugglers Oxford. Arsenal beat Sunderland 2-1 at Highbury, while Liverpool are held to a 1-1 draw at Blackburn.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-05.html]</ref>\n\n6 January 1991 - Fourth Division [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] attract more than 20,000 fans to [[Turf Moor]], where they see [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] win the FA Cup third round tie 1-0. [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], hopeful of following their Second Division rivals Leeds into the First Division for the first time, attract a crowd of more than 22,000 to [[Oakwell]] to watch a 1-1 draw. Last season's beaten finalists Crystal Palace draw 0-0 with Nottingham Forest.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-06.html]</ref>\n\n7 January 1991 - Manchester United begin their defence of the FA Cup with a 2-1 home win over QPR.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-07.html]</ref>\n\n8 January 1991 - Liverpool sign winger [[Jimmy Carter (footballer)|Jimmy Carter]] from [[Millwall F.C.|Milwall]] for \u00a3800,000, on the same day that they beat Blackburn 3-0 in the FA Cup third round replay at Anfield to keep their hopes of a unique second double firmly on track.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-08.html]</ref> Brian Talbot is sacked as West Bromwich Albion manager following their shock FA Cup defeat.\n\n9 January 1991 - In front of a smaller crowd than the one which saw them draw 1-1 at Oakwell three days ago, Leeds beat Barnsley 4-0 in the FA Cup third round replay at Elland Road. The other replays see Coventry beat Wigan 1-0 at [[Springfield Park (Wigan)|Springfield Park]] and Wimbledon beat Aston Villa 1-0 at [[Plough Lane]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-09.html]</ref>\n\n10 January 1991 \u2013 34-year-old former England defender [[Viv Anderson]] joins Second Division promotion chasers Sheffield Wednesday on a free transfer from Manchester United.<ref>http://www.soccerbase.com/transfers_by_value.sd?lower_value=&higher_value=100000000&seasonid=120&x=31&y=4| {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n12 January 1991 - Liverpool remain top of the table but drop two points when they are held to a goalless draw at Aston Villa. Arsenal miss the chance to go top when they are held to a goalless draw in the [[North London derby]] at [[White Hart Lane]]. [[Matthew Le Tissier]] and [[Rod Wallace]] score two goals each in Southampton's 4-3 win at Luton. Manchester United remain in the top five with a 3-0 home win over Sunderland.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-12.html]</ref>\n\n13 January 1991 - Everton win 2-0 at Goodison Park in Howard Kendall's first match in charge against his old club Manchester City.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-13.html]</ref>\n\n15 January 1991 - Liverpool sign 17-year-old midfielder [[Jamie Redknapp]] from [[AFC Bournemouth]] for \u00a3350,000.\n\n16 January 1991 - Leeds United beat Aston Villa 4-1 in the FA Cup quarter final, while Southampton take Manchester United to a replay with a 1-1 draw, while the clash between Chelsea and Tottenham also goes to a replay after the first match at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] ends in a goalless draw. In the only league action of the day, Newcastle's woes continue when they lose 4-2 at Brighton in the Second Division, a result which lifts the [[South Coast of England|South Coast]] club into the playoff zone.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-16.html]</ref>\n\n17 January 1991 \u2013 Sheffield United pay a club record \u00a3450,000 for Crystal Palace midfielder [[Glyn Hodges]], who played under Blades manager [[Dave Bassett]] several years ago when he was in charge at Wimbledon.<ref name=\"soccerbase1\"/>\n\n19 January 1991 - Arsenal go top of the First Division for the first time this season with a 1-0 home win over Everton, while Liverpool (who still have a game in hand) can only manage a 1-1 draw at home to Wimbledon. Crystal Palace's title hopes are hit by a 3-1 home defeat to Norwich.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-19.html]</ref>\n\n23 January 1991 - Chelsea go through to the League semi-finals with a 3-0 win their quarter-final replay at Tottenham. [[Mark Hughes]] scores a hat-trick for Manchester United in their 3-2 replay win over Southampton at Old Trafford which takes them to this stage of the competition for the first time in eight seasons, while 20-year-old striker [[Alan Shearer]] scores twice for the losing side. Sheffield Wednesday win 1-0 at Coventry in their delayed quarter-final tie.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-23.html]</ref>\n\n26 January 1991 - The first FA Cup fourth round ties are played. Second Division promotion rivals Millwall and Sheffield Wednesday clash in [[South London]] and battle out a dramatic 4-4 draw. A South Coast clash sees Portsmouth beat [[AFC Bournemouth]] 5-1 at Fratton Park. Manchester United beat [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] 1-0 at Old Trafford. The only First Division action of the day sees Sheffield United beat Derby 1-0 at [[Bramall Lane]] to boost their survival bid.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-26.html]</ref>\n\n27 January 1991 \u2013 Woking's FA Cup dream comes to an end in the fourth round when they lose 1\u20130 to Everton at [[Goodison Park]]. Arsenal and Leeds draw 0-0 in their fourth round clash at Highbury.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-27.html]</ref>\n\n28 January 1991 - Nottingham Forest beat Crystal Palace 3-0 in their second FA Cup third round replay at the [[City Ground]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-28.html]</ref>\n\n29 January 1991 \u2013 [[David Pleat]] is sacked after three years as manager of [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], the Second Division strugglers.<ref name=\"soccerbase.com\">[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=351 David Pleat | Latest Betting Odds]. Soccer Base. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627050543/http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=351 |date=27 June 2009 }}</ref> His assistant [[Gordon Lee (footballer)|Gordon Lee]], the former Everton manager, is placed in temporary charge.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=546 Gordon Lee | Latest Betting Odds]. Soccer Base. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n30 January 1991 - [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] sign striker [[David Speedie]] from [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] for \u00a3675,000.\n\n31 January 1991 \u2013 Arsenal are one point ahead of Liverpool, who have a game in hand, at the top of the First Division. Meanwhile, Crystal Palace are still in contention for a first-ever league title, six points off the top, while Sheffield United remain bottom.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> West Ham United, Oldham Athletic and Sheffield Wednesday continue to occupy the top three places in the Second Division. Notts County, Middlesbrough, Brighton and Millwall occupy the playoff zone.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=19&Month=Jan&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1991-01-19). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 February 1991 \u2013 [[Paul Birch (footballer, born 1962)|Paul Birch]] leaves [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] after 10 years to join [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] for \u00a3400,000.<ref name=\"Soccer Base\"/>\n\n2 February 1991 \u2013 Arsenal suffer their first league defeat of the season in their 24th game, going down 2\u20131 to Chelsea at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> They remain top of the league by a single point, although Liverpool have two games in hand. Sheffield United are now just two points adrift of safety after a 4-1 home win over Southampton. In the Second Division, Oldham suffer a shock 5-1 defeat at Oxford.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-02-02.html]</ref>\n\n12 February 1991 \u2013 Aston Villa sign defender [[Neil Cox (footballer)|Neil Cox]] from [[Scunthorpe United]] for \u00a3400,000, a record fee for a Fourth Division player.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://www.soccerbase.com/transfers_by_value.sd?lower_value=&higher_value=100000000&seasonid=120&x=31&y=4 Football Betting | Place Your Football Bet Today | Soccer Base] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n17 February 1991 - Liverpool and Everton draw 0-0 in an [[Merseyside derby|all Merseyside]] FA Cup fifth round tie at [[Anfield]].\n\n20 February 1991 \u2013 Sheffield Wednesday sign 19-year-old striker [[Gordon Watson (footballer, born 1971)|Gordon Watson]] from [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] for \u00a3250,000. The FA Cup fourth round replay between Liverpool ends in a dramatic 4-4 draw at [[Goodison Park]], forcing a second replay.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n21 February 1991 - In a record fee for a non-league player, [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] striker [[Andy Clarke (footballer)|Andy Clarke]] joins [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] for \u00a3250,000.\n\n22 February 1991 \u2013 [[Kenny Dalglish]] announces his resignation as Liverpool manager. Long-serving coach [[Ronnie Moran]] is appointed caretaker manager. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n24 February 1991 - Arsenal return to the top of the First Division on goal difference, beating Crystal Palace 4-0 at Highbury, while Liverpool suffer a shock 3-1 defeat at Luton. Wimbledon go sixth with a 5-1 win over Tottenham at Plough Lane.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-02-23.html]</ref> In the first leg of the League Cup semi finals, Sheffield Wednesday win 2-0 at Chelsea and Manchester United win 1-0 at Leeds.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-02-24.html]</ref>\n\n27 February 1991 - Everton beat Liverpool 1-0 in the second replay of the FA Cup fifth round tie at Goodison Park, ending Liverpool's hopes of a unique second double. Sheffield Wednesday reach their first cup final in 25 years by beating Chelsea 3-1 in the League Cup semi-final second leg.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-02-27.html]</ref>\n\n28 February 1991 \u2013 February draws to a close with Arsenal now ahead of Liverpool at the top of the First Division on goal difference, while Crystal Palace are five points behind. At the other end of the table, a splendid run of form has moved Sheffield United six points clear of bottom-placed Derby County. The Blades are level on goal difference with Coventry City, Sunderland and Queens Park Rangers.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> West Ham United, Oldham Athletic and Sheffield Wednesday continue to lead the way in the Second Division. Middlesbrough, Notts County, Brighton and Millwall occupy the playoff zone, with Bristol City continuing to turn up the heat on them in their bid for a second successive promotion.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=23&Month=Feb&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1991-02-23). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\nMarch - [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] captain [[Alan Hansen]] retires after 14 years at the club, having been out of action for almost a year due to injury.\n\n2 March 1991 - Manchester United give Ryan Giggs his senior debut as a substitute in a league match at Old Trafford, which ends in a 2-0 defeat to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. [[Dean Saunders]] scores a hat-trick for Derby in a 3-3 relegation crunch clash with Sunderland at the Baseball Ground.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-02.html]</ref>\n\n3 March 1991 \u2013 Arsenal move three points clear at the top of the First Division by beating Liverpool 1\u20130 at Anfield thanks to a goal by [[Paul Merson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/SeasonArchive/Game/1778|title=Matchdetails from Liverpool - Arsenal played on Sunday 3 March 1991 - LFChistory - Stats galore for Liverpool FC!|first=|last=LFChistory.net|date=|website=www.lfchistory.net|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n16 March 1991 - Liverpool go back to the top of the First Division by beating Sunderland 2-1 at Anfield.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-16.html]</ref>\n\n17 March 1991 - Arsenal return to the top of the First Division on goal difference (with a game in hand) by beating Leeds 2-0 at Highbury.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-17.html]</ref>\n\n20 March 1991 \u2013 Swindon Town sell defender [[Paul Bodin]] to Crystal Palace for \u00a3550,000.<ref name=\"Soccer Base\"/>\n\n22 March 1991 - [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] sign striker [[Robert Rosario]] from [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] for \u00a3600,000.\n\n23 March 1991 \u2013 Liverpool beat Derby County 7\u20131 at the [[Baseball Ground]], the first time in 28 years that a First Division team has scored seven goals away from home.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Arsenal's goalless draw at Norwich sends Liverpool back to the top of the table.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-23.html]</ref>\n\n26 March 1991 - [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] sign [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet]] winger [[Andrei Kanchelskis]], 22, from [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk]] for \u00a31million. [[Ossie Ardiles]] leaves [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] to become the new manager of [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] following the resignation of [[Jim Smith (footballer, born 1940)|Jim Smith]].\n\n27 March 1991 - In the only league game of the day, Oldham and West Ham remain locked together at the top of the Second Division after a 1-1 draw at [[Boundary Park]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-29.html]</ref>\n\n28 March 1991 \u2013 The 90-day inquest into the [[Hillsborough disaster]] records a verdict of accidental death on the 95 Liverpool fans who died as a result of their injuries at the FA Cup semi-final on 15 April 1989.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/march/28/newsid_2531000/2531015.stm BBC ON THIS DAY | 28 | 1991: Family anger at Hillsborough verdict]. BBC News. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n30 March 1991 \u2013 Manchester United centre-back [[Steve Bruce]] scores twice in a 3\u20130 away league win over his old club Norwich City, becoming the first defender to score ten league goals this season.<ref>[http://www.manchester-united-fans-site.com/manchester-united-results-1990-1991.html Manchester United Results 1990\u20131991, Division One, FA Cup, League Cup, European] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126223849/http://www.manchester-united-fans-site.com/manchester-united-results-1990-1991.html |date=2010-11-26 }}. Manchester-united-fans-site.com. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref> Arsenal return to the top of the First Division by beating Derby 2-0 at the Baseball Ground, while Liverpool suffer a shock 3-1 defeat at home to QPR.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-30.html]</ref>\n\n31 March 1991 \u2013 March draws to a close with Arsenal leading Liverpool by two points. Sheffield United's incredible revival has continued as they now stand 12th in the table, but Derby County are twelve points adrift of safety, and Sunderland occupy the other relegation place.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Oldham Athletic and West Ham United lead the Second Division level on 70 points, with Brighton, Middlesbrough, Millwall and Bristol City occupying the playoff zone. [[Ossie Ardiles]] becomes manager of Newcastle United, who are just six points outside the playoff zone with two games in hand.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=29&Month=Mar&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1991-03-29). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 April 1991 \u2013 Liverpool's hopes of retaining their league title are damaged by a 1\u20130 away defeat to Southampton.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/>\n\n3 April 1991 - Arsenal are five points ahead at the top of the First Division with seven games remaining after a 5-0 home win over Aston Villa.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-04-03.html]</ref>\n\n6 April 1991 - Arsenal take a step closer to the title by beating Sheffield United 2-0 at [[Bramall Lane]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-04-06.html]</ref>\n\n7 April 1991 \u2013 Crystal Palace win the [[Full Members Cup]] after a 4-1 victory over Everton in the Wembley final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/full-members-cup/1990-1991/results/1991-04 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100219151435/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/full-members-cup/1990-1991/results/1991-04 |archivedate=2010-02-19 }}</ref>\n\n13 April 1991 \u2013 Liverpool's title challenge is kept alive with a thrilling 5\u20134 away win over Leeds United, but the Reds are five points behind Arsenal with five games left. Leeds striker [[Lee Chapman]] finds himself in the unusual position of scoring a hat-trick despite being on the losing side.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/><ref>[http://www.liverweb.org.uk/season.asp?season=199091 Liverpool Results 1990\u201391] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218135945/http://www.liverweb.org.uk/season.asp?season=199091 |date=2012-02-18 }}. Liverweb. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n14 April 1991 \u2013 Tottenham Hotspur end Arsenal's hopes of the double and boost their own hopes of an eighth FA Cup triumph with a 3\u20131 win in the first FA Cup semi-final to be played at Wembley. Nottingham Forest win the other semi-final, crushing West Ham United 4\u20130 at [[Villa Park]].\n\n16 April 1991 \u2013 [[Graeme Souness]] is named as Liverpool's new manager, departing from Rangers, where he is succeeded by [[Walter Smith (footballer)|Walter Smith]]. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n20 April 1991 \u2013 Nottingham Forest record the biggest First Division win of the season by beating Chelsea 7\u20130 at the [[City Ground]].<ref>[http://www.statto.com/football/teams/nottingham-forest/1990-1991/results Nottingham Forest 1990\u20131991 : Results. League Results] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051449/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/nottingham-forest/1990-1991/results |date=March 4, 2016 }}</ref> Derby County lose to Manchester City and are relegated.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> West Ham seal promotion back to the First Division two years after relegation by beating Swindon 2-0 at Upton Park, with five games left to play in the Second Division.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-04-20.html]</ref>\n\n21 April 1991 \u2013 Sheffield Wednesday, chasing promotion to the First Division, achieve a 1\u20130 win over Manchester United in the [[1991 Football League Cup Final|League Cup final]] to end a 56-year trophy drought. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n23 April 1991 - [[David White (English footballer)|David White]] scores four goals for Manchester City in a 5-2 away win over Aston Villa. With three games to go, the title race remains open as both Arsenal and Liverpool win and the gap remains three points wide.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-04-23.html]</ref>\n\n27 April 1919 - Oldham Athletic are promoted to the First Division after 68-year exile by beating Ipswich Town 2-1 a to [[Portman Road]].<ref>[https://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/2017/april/on-this-day-april-27-1991/]</ref>\n\n30 April 1991 \u2013 April draws to a close with Arsenal three points ahead of Liverpool with three matches left, while Crystal Palace's title dreams have ended. Sunderland, Luton Town and last season's runners-up Aston Villa still fighting to avoid relegation alongside Derby County.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/>\n\n1 May 1991 \u2013 England beat [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] 1\u20130 in [[Izmir]] in their fourth European Championship qualifying game. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n4 May 1991 \u2013 Arsenal edge closer to the title by drawing 0\u20130 with Sunderland, while Liverpool are beaten 4\u20132 by Chelsea.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/>\n\n6 May 1991 \u2013 Liverpool are beaten 2\u20131 by Nottingham Forest, handing the title to Arsenal,<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> who beat Manchester United 3\u20131. [[Alan Smith (footballer born 1962)|Alan Smith]] scores a hat-trick.<ref name=\"arseweb.com\">[http://www.arseweb.com/history/stats/91.html Arsenal appearances 1990/91]. Arseweb.com. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n8 May 1991 - Aston Villa, First Division runners-up last season, confirm their survival with a 2-1 win at home to Norwich City. Sheffield Wednesday seal an immediate return to the First Division with a 3-1 home win over Bristol City.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-05-08.html]</ref>\n\n11 May 1991 \u2013 Sunderland are relegated to the Second Division as they lose to Manchester City and Luton Town beat Derby County 2\u20130. It is the second season running that Luton have survived on the last day of the season with victory over Derby.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Arsenal end their championship campaign with a 6\u20131 demolition of Coventry City at Highbury, with [[Anders Limpar]] scoring a hat-trick.<ref name=\"arseweb.com\"/> The Second Division campaign ended with Oldham Athletic, already promoted to the First Division for the first time since 1923, crowned as champions thanks to an injury-time final-day Neil Redfearn penalty earning them a 3-2 comeback victory over Sheffield Wednesday. West Ham United, last day losers to 4th-place Notts County, had to settle for second. Sheffield Wednesday took the third automatic promotion spot. Hull City's relegation was confirmed 2 weeks ago, while West Bromwich Albion are relegated alongside them to fall into the Third Division for the first time in their history.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=11&Month=May&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1991-05-11). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n13 May 1991 - Gerry Francis resigns after four years as manager of Bristol Rovers, despite having guided the club a mid table finish in the Second Division a year after winning promotion.\n\n15 May 1991 \u2013 Manchester United mark the return to European football by English clubs with a 2\u20131 win over [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the [[1991 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|European Cup Winners' Cup final]] in [[Rotterdam]]. [[Mark Hughes]] scores both goals. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n18 May 1991 \u2013 Tottenham Hotspur win the FA Cup for the eighth time, beating Nottingham Forest 2\u20131 after extra time in the [[1991 FA Cup Final|final]]. [[Paul Gascoigne]] suffers cruciate knee ligament damage, causing his proposed \u00a38.5million move to Lazio to be put on hold.<ref>[http://www.newsint-archive.co.uk/pages/S.asp?pubsel=BOTH&SrchText=Gascoigne+and+Lazio&edn=&DateFromDD=01&DateFromMM=Jul&DateFromYY=1990&page=&SortOrder=Asc&SortOrder=asc&SortOrder=asc&SortOrder=asc&SortSpec=&DateToDD=31&DateToMM=May&ResultListMax=200&Submit1=Search&source=thetimes&DateToYY=1991&byline=&head=&Collection=NI%C2%A7%3D&Caption=&SortField=SDate&SortField=Pub&SortField=EDN&SortField=Page&ST=NS&Site=ALL&ResultCount=20&BackDD=Day&summreqd=yes&QueryText=%28Gascoigne+and+Lazio%29+%3CAND%3E+%28PUB%3DBOTH%29+%3CAND%3E+%28%28SDate%3E%3D7%2F1%2F1990%29+%3CAND%3E+%28SDate%3C%3D5%2F31%2F1991%29%29&BackMM=Month&indexkey=90C42980957987041730&advsrch=0&BackYY=Year&_P=3&ResultMaxDocs=200& The Times and The Sunday Times Archive]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Newsint-archive.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n20 May 1991 - The First Division campaign ends with a 1-1 draw between Manchester United and Tottenham at Old Trafford.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-05-20.html]</ref>\n\n21 May 1991 - [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]] manager [[Don Howe]] is sacked after 18 months in charge at [[Loftus Road]].\n\n28 May 1991 - Jozef Venglos leaves Aston Villa after just one season as manager.\n\n30 May 1991 \u2013 [[Brian Little (footballer)|Brian Little]], whose [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] side have just secured their second successive promotion and won the Fourth Division title, is appointed as Leicester City's new manager.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=252 Brian Little | Latest Betting Odds]. Soccer Base. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001043929/http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=252 |date=1 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n31 May 1991 - [[Ron Atkinson]], the [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] manager, turns down an offer to become the new Aston Villa manager. Torquay United win promotion to the Third Division after nearly 20 years in the Fourth Division, beating Blackpool on penalties after a 2-2 draw in the Wembley playoff final.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-05-31.html]</ref>\n\n1 June 1991 - [[Gerry Francis]], who was captain of QPR during the 1970s, returns to Loftus Road as manager. Jim Smith is appointed manager of [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. Tranmere reach the Second Division for the first time since 1938 by beating Bolton 1-0 in the Third Division playoff final.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-06-01.html]</ref>\n\n2 June 1991 \u2013 Notts County beat [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] 3\u20131 in the Second Division play-off final to seal promotion to the First Division - their second successive promotion.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-06-02.html]</ref>\n\n6 June 1991 \u2013 David Pleat is appointed Luton Town manager for the second time.<ref name=\"soccerbase.com\"/> Leeds United pay a club record \u00a31.6million for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] striker [[Rod Wallace]].\n\n7 June 1991 - Ron Atkinson becomes the new Aston Villa manager after accepting an improved offer.\n\n18 June 1991 - Veteran striker [[Trevor Francis]] is appointed player-manager of Sheffield Wednesday.\n\n25 June 1991 - [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], now bankrolled by the wealth of local steel baron [[Jack Walker]], pay a club record \u00a3700,000 for [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] midfielder [[Steve Agnew]].\n\n27 June 1991 \u2013 Former Oldham Athletic goalkeeper [[Andy Goram]] becomes Scotland's first \u00a31million goalkeeper after a move from [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] to [[Rangers F.C.|Glasgow Rangers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=2953|title=Andy Goram - Football Stats - No Club - Age 53 - 1981-2006 - Soccer Base|author=|date=|website=www.soccerbase.com|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==National team==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2019}}\n\n==FA Cup==\n{{Main|1990\u201391 FA Cup}}\n[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] beat [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] 2\u20131 after extra time in the [[1991 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]]. The decisive goal was an own goal by Forest defender [[Des Walker]]. Tottenham's triumph was overshadowed by a knee injury to star midfielder [[Paul Gascoigne]] in the opening 15&nbsp;minutes.\n\n==Football League Cup==\n{{Main|1990\u201391 Football League Cup}}\nSheffield Wednesday earned a shock 1\u20130 victory over their manager Ron Atkinson's old club Manchester United in the [[1991 Football League Cup Final|final]] thanks to a goal from [[John Sheridan (footballer)|John Sheridan]].\n\n==Football League==\n{{main|1990\u201391 Football League}}\n\n===First Division===\n[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] won the First Division after losing just one of their league matches all season. [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] finished runners-up. Third place went to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. Newly promoted [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] had a good season back in the First Division as they finished fourth, and also reached the semi-finals of the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]. At the bottom of the table, [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] went down in last place with just five wins all season despite the 17 league goals of [[Wales|Welsh]] striker [[Dean Saunders]], who was then sold to Liverpool. The other relegation place went to [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].\n{{:1990\u201391 Football League First Division|only_totals=y}}\n\n===Second Division===\n[[Joe Royle]]'s [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] side won the Second Division championship ahead of [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], who were promoted as runners-up. Joining them in promotion were League Cup winners Sheffield Wednesday, who finished in third place. [[Neil Warnock]] guided [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] to a second successive victory in the promotion play-offs. [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] were relegated.\n{{:1990\u201391 Football League|only_totals=y|transcludesection=Second Division}}\n\n====Second Division play-offs====\n\n{{ConfPlayoff | RD1=Semifinals<br>1st leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 19; 2nd leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 22, 1991\n| RD2=Final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]<br>June 2, 1991\n| RD1-seed1='''4th'''\n| RD1-team1='''[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]'''\n| RD1-score1-1=1\n| RD1-score1-2=1\n| RD1-score1-A='''2'''\n| RD1-seed2=7th\n| RD1-team2= [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| RD1-score2-1=1\n| RD1-score2-2=0\n| RD1-score2-A=1\n| RD1-seed3=5th\n| RD1-team3= [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n| RD1-score3-1=1\n| RD1-score3-2=1\n| RD1-score3-A=2\n| RD1-seed4='''6th'''\n| RD1-team4='''[[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]'''\n| RD1-score4-1=4\n| RD1-score4-2=2\n| RD1-score4-A='''5'''\n| RD2-seed1='''4th'''\n| RD2-team1='''[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]'''\n| RD2-score1='''3'''\n| RD2-seed2=6th\n| RD2-team2= [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| RD2-score2= 1\n}}\n\n===Third Division===\nChampions [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]], runners-up [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] and third-placed [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] occupied the automatic promotion places and all achieved second successive promotions. The fourth promotion place went to play-off winners [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]. Going down to the Fourth Division were [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] and [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]].\n{{:1990\u201391 Football League|only_totals=y|transcludesection=Third Division}}\n\n====Third Division play-offs====\nThe semifinals were decided over two legs, and only the aggregates are given in the schemata below. The final consisted of only a single match.<br>The full results can be found at: [[Football League One play-offs#1991|Football League Division Three play-offs 1991]].\n\n{{ConfPlayoff | RD1=Semifinals<br>1st leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 19; 2nd leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 22, 1991\n| RD2=Final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]<br>June 1, 1991\n| RD1-seed1='''4th'''\n| RD1-team1='''[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]'''\n| RD1-score1-1=1\n| RD1-score1-2=1\n| RD1-score1-A='''2'''\n| RD1-seed2=7th\n| RD1-team2=[[Bury F.C.|Bury]]\n| RD1-score2-1=1\n| RD1-score2-2=0\n| RD1-score2-A= 1\n| RD1-seed3='''5th'''\n| RD1-team3='''[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]'''\n| RD1-score3-1=2\n| RD1-score3-2=1\n| RD1-score3-A='''3'''\n| RD1-seed4=6th\n| RD1-team4=[[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| RD1-score4-1=2\n| RD1-score4-2=0\n| RD1-score4-A= 2\n| RD2-seed1=4th\n| RD2-team1=[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| RD2-score1= 0\n| RD2-seed2='''5th'''\n| RD2-team2='''[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]''' {{aet}}\n| RD2-score2='''1'''\n}}\n\n===Fourth Division===\nBrian Little's [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] won the Fourth Division championship to earn a second successive promotion, while the other four promotion places went to [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]], [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] and [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]. Torquay were the play-off winners, beating [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in a penalty shoot-out in the final. {{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n[[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]] finished bottom of the league, but avoided relegation into the Conference as the Football League increased in size from 92 to 93 teams for 1991-92.\n{{:1990\u201391 Football League|only_totals=y|transcludesection=Fourth Division}}\n\n====Fourth Division play-offs====\n\n{{ConfPlayoff | RD1=Semifinals<br>1st leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 19; 2nd leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 22, 1991\n| RD2=Final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]<br>May 31, 1991\n| RD1-seed1='''5th'''\n| RD1-team1='''[[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]'''\n| RD1-score1-1=1\n| RD1-score1-2=2\n| RD1-score1-A='''3'''\n| RD1-seed2=8th\n| RD1-team2=[[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]\n| RD1-score2-1=1\n| RD1-score2-2=1\n| RD1-score2-A=2\n| RD1-seed3=6th\n| RD1-team3=[[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n| RD1-score3-1=0\n| RD1-score3-2=1\n| RD1-score3-A=1\n| RD1-seed4='''7th'''\n| RD1-team4='''[[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]'''\n| RD1-score4-1=2\n| RD1-score4-2=0\n| RD1-score4-A='''2'''\n| RD2-seed1=5th\n| RD2-team1=[[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]\n| RD2-score1=2 (4)\n| RD2-seed2='''7th'''\n| RD2-team2='''[[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]''' ([[Penalty shootout (association football)|pen.]])\n| RD2-score2='''2 (5)'''\n}}\n\n===Top goalscorers===\n\n'''First Division'''\n* [[Alan Smith (footballer born 1962)|Alan Smith]] ([[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]) \u2013 22 goals<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html English League Leading Goalscorers] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628202228/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html |date=June 28, 2011 }}. Rsssf.com (2010-09-17). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n'''Second Division'''\n* [[Teddy Sheringham]] ([[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]) \u2013 38 goals\n\n'''Third Division'''\n* [[Brett Angell]] ([[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]])/[[Tony Philliskirk]] ([[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]) \u2013 26 goals\n\n'''Fourth Division'''\n* [[Steve Norris (footballer)|Steve Norris]] ([[Halifax Town F.C.|Halifax Town]]) \u2013 35 goals\n\n==Non-league football==\nThe divisional champions of the major non-League competitions were:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Competition!!Winners\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Football Conference|Football Conference]]\n|[[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Isthmian League|Isthmian League]]\n|[[Redbridge Forest F.C.|Redbridge Forest]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Northern Premier League|Northern Premier League]]\n|[[Witton Albion F.C.|Witton Albion]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Southern Football League|Southern League]]\n|[[Farnborough Town F.C.|Farnborough Town]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 FA Trophy|FA Trophy]]\n|[[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 FA Vase|FA Vase]]\n|[[Guiseley F.C.|Guiseley]]\n|}\n\n==Retirements==\n* [[Tommy Hutchison]], 43-year-old midfielder with one of the highest appearance records of any player in English football, played his final game for [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on 12 March 1991 against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] in the Third Division.<ref>[http://www.swanseacity-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadtmrs.asp?ssnno=120&teamno=508 Fixtures/Results \u2013 Swansea City FC \u2013 Swansea MAD]. Swanseacity-mad.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n* [[Jim Beglin]], 27-year-old [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] and [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] left-back formerly with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], retires after failing to overcome a long-term knee injury.<ref>[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=36421 Jim Beglin \u2013 Liverpool FC \u2013 Football-Heroes.net]. Sporting-heroes.net. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n* [[Alan Hansen]], 35-year-old Liverpool captain and former [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] international, retires after a year out of action with injury.\n* [[Norman Whiteside]], 26-year-old [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] attacking midfielder, formerly of Manchester United, retires due to a knee injury.<ref>[http://www.newsint-archive.co.uk/pages/S.asp?pubsel=BOTH&SrchText=whiteside&DateFromDD=01&DateFromMM=Aug&DateFromYY=1990&DateToDD=31&DateToMM=Jul&DateToYY=1991&ResultListMax=200&head=&byline=&sect=&Caption=&edn=&page=&SortOrder=Asc&SortField=SDate&Submit1=Search&BackDD=Day&BackMM=Month&BackYY=Year&source=thetimes&SortField=Pub&SortOrder=asc&SortField=EDN&SortOrder=asc&SortField=Page&SortOrder=asc&ST=NS&SortSpec=&ResultMaxDocs=200&Site=ALL&Collection=NI&ResultCount=20&summreqd=yes&indexkey=145B6565996913733050&advsrch=0&QueryText=%28whiteside%29+%3CAND%3E+%28PUB%3DBOTH%29+%3CAND%3E+%28%28SDate%3E%3D8%2F1%2F1990%29+%3CAND%3E+%28SDate%3C%3D7%2F31%2F1991%29%29&_P=1 The Times and The Sunday Times Archive]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Newsint-archive.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n\nJuly 1990 - [[Eric Anderson (English footballer)|Eric Anderson]], 59, played for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] as a forward during the 1950s.\n\n23 July 1990 - [[Dave Deacon]], 61, played 66 league games for [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], many of them under the management of [[Alf Ramsey]], and later played for [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] when they were still a non-league team.\n\n9 August 1990 - [[Joe Mercer]], 76, who won a total of three league titles as a player with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] (1939) and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] (1948 and 1953), and was later manager of [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], as well as an interim spell as manager of the [[England national football team]] in 1974.\n\n15 August 1990 - [[Billy Hume]], 54, spent most of his career in his native [[Scotland]] but made 10 appearances as a forward for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] between 1958 and 1960.\n\n17 August 1990 - [[Ian Handysides]], 27, former [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] and [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]] forward, died of cancer after a two-year battle against the illness.\n\n20 August 1990 -\n\n** - [[Fred Bennett]], 83, played a total of 287 league games at full-back during the interwar years for [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] and [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]].\n** - [[Bill Curry]], 54, played 391 games as a forward between 1953 and 1969 for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], Brighton, Derby County, [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] and [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]].\n\n8 September 1990 - [[David Longhurst]], 25, [[York City F.C.|York City]] striker, died after collapsing during a Fourth Division fixture at home to Lincoln City.\n\n5 October 1990 - [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1928)|Peter Taylor]], 62, most famous for serving as assistant manager to [[Brian Clough]] at [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] between 1965 and 1982. Also had a spell as manager of non-league [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] before linking up with Clough, and later returned to Derby as manager from 1982 to 1984.\n\n28 November 1990 - [[Ted Catlin]], 79, played more than 200 games at left-back for [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] during the 1930s and picked up an [[FA Cup]] winner's medal in 1935, also winning five caps for England.\n\nDecember 1990 - [[Pat Jones (footballer)|Pat Jones]], 70, played 425 league games for [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] as a full-back between 1946 and 1957.\n\n22 December 1990 - [[Robin Friday]], 38, who was found dead from heart attack in his [[London]] flat, was a striker for [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] during the 1970s.\n\n24 December 1990 - [[Don Dearson]], 76, played 131 league games for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] during a career which was disrupted by the Second World War, before spending the final few seasons of his career with [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]].\n\n25 January 1991 - [[Frank Soo]], 76, played 173 league games at half-back for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] before the Second World War and 71 times for [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] in the early postwar league campaigns. He later managed 12 different British and overseas club sides and had a brief spell in charge of the [[Norway national football team]].\n\nApril 1991 - [[Bobby Baxter (footballer, born 1911)|Bobby Baxter]], 80, played 247 league games for [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] during the 1930s before completing his league career in his native [[Scotland]] with [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] in the immediate postwar era.\n\nMay 1991 - [[Harold Hobbis]], 78, made 248 league appearances for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] as a winger between 1931 and 1948, and scored one goal in two pre-war appearances for the England team.\n\n22 May 1991 - [[Stan Mortensen]], 69, former [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] forward who scored over 200 goals for the club all competitions, winning the [[FA Cup]] in 1953 and also scoring 23 goals in 25 games for the [[England national football team|England team]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{trim|{{suppress categories|{{English football seasons|1990}}}}}}\n{{1990\u201391 in English football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1990-91 in English football}}\n[[Category:1990\u201391 in English football| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox football country season\n| country     = England\n| season      = 1990\u201391\n| division1   = [[1990\u201391 Football League First Division|First Division]]\n| champions1  = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| division2   = [[1990\u201391 Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n| champions2  = [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]]\n| division3   = [[1990\u201391 Football League Third Division|Third Division]]\n| champions3  = [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]\n| division4   = [[1990\u201391 Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]]\n| champions4  = [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]]\n| division5   = [[1990\u201391 Football Conference|Football Conference]]\n| champions5  = [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n| domestic    = [[1990\u201391 FA Cup|FA Cup]]\n| dchampions  = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n| domestic2   = [[1990\u201391 Associate Members' Cup|Associate Members' Cup]]\n| dchampions2 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n| leaguecup   = [[1990\u201391 Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n| lchampions  = [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]\n| supercup    = [[1990 FA Charity Shield|Charity Shield]]\n| schampions  = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] & [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n| prevseason  = 1989\u201390\n| nextseason  = 1991\u201392\n| flagicon    = yes\n}}\nThe '''1990\u201391''' season was the 111th season of competitive [[football (soccer)|football]] in England.\n\n==Diary of the season==\n\n2 July 1990 - [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] prepare for their First Division comeback by signing midfielder [[Gary McAllister]] from [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] for \u00a31million.\n\n3 July 1990 - [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] pay a club record \u00a31.6million for [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] winger [[Dennis Wise]].\n\n4 July 1990 - [[England national football team|England's]] World Cup hopes are ended in a semi-final defeat by [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]], with [[Chris Waddle]] and [[Stuart Pearce]] both missing penalties.\n\n5 July 1990 - Chelsea sign [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] midfielder [[Andy Townsend]] for \u00a31.2million.\n\n16 July 1990 - [[Graham Taylor]], manager of [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], is appointed as successor to [[Bobby Robson]] as the England manager.\n\n18 July 1990 - [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] sign defender [[Paul Blades]] from Norwich City for \u00a3700,000.\n\n19 July 1990 - England striker [[Mark Hateley]] ends six years overseas and joins Scottish league champions [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in a \u00a31million move from [[AS Monaco]]. He had played on the continent since his move from [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] to [[AC Milan]] in 1984.\n\n20 July 1990 \u2013 Manchester City pay a club record \u00a31 million for [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] goalkeeper [[Tony Coton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=1718&comp_id=1&teamTabs=transfers|title=Latest Man City Transfers - Full Transfer History - Soccer Base|author=|date=|website=www.soccerbase.com|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n22 July 1990 - [[Czechoslovakia|Czech]] national coach [[Jozef Venglos]] is appointed as the new manager of Aston Villa, and becomes the first foreign manager in the First Division.\n\n31 July 1990 - [[Aldershot F.C.]] in the Fourth Division are wound up in the High Court, condemned as \"hopelessly insolvent\" with debts of nearly \u00a3500,000 by the Official Receiver.\n\n1 August 1990 \u2013\n\n* - The [[Football League]] confirms that it will revert to a 22-club First Division for the [[1991\u201392 in English football|1991\u201392 season]], while total league membership will be increased to 94 clubs for the 1992\u201393 season, with the Second, Third and Fourth Divisions each having 24 clubs.\n* - [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] sell striker [[Dalian Atkinson]] to [[Real Sociedad]] of [[Spain]] for \u00a31million, where he will be playing alongside the former [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] striker [[John Aldridge]]. Long-serving [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] defender [[Mike Duxbury]] joins [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on a free transfer.\n\n6 August 1990 - [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] sign [[Sweden|Swedish]] winger [[Anders Limpar]] from Italian side [[Cremonese]] for \u00a31million.\n\n7 August 1990 \u2013 Aldershot are saved from closure by a \u00a3200,000 rescue package put together by 19-year-old property developer [[Spencer Trethewy]], which means that they will be able to start the new Football League season.<ref name=\"mirrorfootball.co.uk\">[http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/blogs/mirror-football-blog/Newcastle-s-Freddy-Shepherd-Chelsea-s-Ken-Bates-Leeds-Peter-Ridsdale-Palace-s-Simon-Jordan-and-the-Top-10-crazy-football-chairman-article320687.html Newcastle's Freddy Shepherd, Chelsea's Ken Bates, Leeds' Peter Ridsdale, Palace's Simon Jordan and the Top 10 crazy football chairman \u2013 Mirror Football Blog]. MirrorFootball.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n15 August 1990 - [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] sign [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] defender [[Eric Young (footballer, born 1960)|Eric Young]] for \u00a3850,000.\n\n16 August 1990 - Crystal Palace further strengthen their defence with a \u00a3400,000 move for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], their [[Selhurst Park]] tenants, for [[John Humphrey (footballer)|John Humphrey]].\n\n18 August 1990 \u2013 Liverpool and Manchester United share the [[1990 FA Charity Shield|Charity Shield]] after a 1\u20131 draw at Wembley.\n\n23 August 1990 \u2013 [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] pay a club record \u00a3460,000 for [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] striker [[David Currie (footballer)|David Currie]]. [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] are warned that they face expulsion from the Football League if measures aimed by the Football Association at curbing incidents of hooliganism involving the club's fans fail.<ref>[http://www.newsint-archive.co.uk/pages/S.asp?pubsel=BOTH&SrchText=football+and+hooligans&DateFromDD=01&DateFromMM=Aug&DateFromYY=1990&DateToDD=31&DateToMM=Jul&DateToYY=1991&ResultListMax=200&head=&byline=&sect=&Caption=&edn=&page=&SortOrder=Asc&SortField=SDate&Submit1=Search&BackDD=Day&BackMM=Month&BackYY=Year&source=thetimes&SortField=Pub&SortOrder=asc&SortField=EDN&SortOrder=asc&SortField=Page&SortOrder=asc&ST=NS&SortSpec=&ResultMaxDocs=200&Site=ALL&Collection=NI&ResultCount=20&summreqd=yes&indexkey=31C3128516001143593E190&advsrch=0&QueryText=%28football+and+hooligans%29+%3CAND%3E+%28PUB%3DBOTH%29+%3CAND%3E+%28%28SDate%3E%3D8%2F1%2F1990%29+%3CAND%3E+%28SDate%3C%3D7%2F31%2F1991%29%29&_P=1 The Times and The Sunday Times Archive]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Newsint-archive.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n24 August 1990 - [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] sign midfielder [[Mike Milligan (footballer)|Mike Milligan]] from [[Oldham Athletic]] for \u00a31million.\n\n25 August 1990 \u2013 Liverpool begin their defence of the First Division title with a 3\u20131 away win against recently promoted [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\">{{cite book|last=Smailes|first=Gordon|title=The Breedon Book of Football Records|year=2000|publisher=Breedon Books|location=Derby|isbn=1859832148|pages=166}}</ref>[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] begin their challenge for a second league title in three seasons by beating [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] 3-0 at [[Plough Lane]]. [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] enjoy a fine First Division comeback with a 3-2 away win over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. Key games on the opening day of the Second Division campaign include a 4-2 home win over [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] for newly promoted [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] and [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United's]] 5-2 home win over [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]. In the Fourth Division, [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] draw 2-2 with [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]] in their first game at the new [[Bescot Stadium]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-08-25.html]</ref>\n\n28 August 1990 - [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and Leeds United meet for the first time since April 1982, and battle out a goalless draw at [[Elland Road]] in the First Division - a repeat of the last clash between the two sides.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-08-28.html]</ref>\n\n31 August 1990 \u2013 The first month of the English league season ends with Arsenal and Liverpool sharing the lead in the First Division after two games.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> The Second Division leaders are Oldham Athletic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics MAD |author=Entertainment & Sports Agency Limited |url=http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=28&Month=Aug&ssnno=120&teamno=404 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007113745/http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=28&Month=Aug&ssnno=120&teamno=404 |archivedate=2011-10-07 |url-status=live |accessdate=2009-05-17 }}</ref>\n\n1 September 1990 \u2013 Newly promoted First Division side [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] achieve a shock 2\u20131 league win over FA Cup holders Manchester United at [[Roker Park]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Liverpool's 3-1 home win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] leaves them with the only 100% record in the First Division after three games. Leeds go second with a 3-0 home win over [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]. Everton's 1-0 defeat to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] at [[Maine Road]] leaves with without a point from their opening three games. There are victories in the Second Division for promotion favourites [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-01.html]</ref>\n\n4 September 1990 - The only league action of the day sees a [[Mark Robins]] goal give Manchester United a 1-0 away win over [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-04.html]</ref>\n\n8 September 1990 - Liverpool extend their winning start to the season to four games with a 2-1 away win over Wimbledon. Mark Robins is the star of the show for Manchester United once again, scoring twice in a 3-1 home win over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]]. [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] go second with a 3-0 win at Norwich. [[Paul Gascoigne]] scores a hat-trick for [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] in their 3-0 home win over [[Derby County F.C.|Derby]]. Everton claim their first point of the season with a 1-1 draw at home to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Oldham have a 100% record after four games, remaining top of the Second Division with a 1-0 win at [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-08.html]</ref>\n\n10 September 1990 - Manager [[Joe Jordan]] leaves Bristol City to return to his native [[Scotland]] and become manager of [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]].\n\n12 September 1990 \u2013 England beat [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] 1\u20130 in a friendly at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]], the first game under Graham Taylor's management. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n15 September 1990 - Arsenal keep up the pressure on Liverpool with a 4-1 home win over Chelsea, as do Tottenham with a 2-0 win at Leeds. Oldham make it five wins in a row in the Second Division by beating Oxford 3-0 at [[Boundary Park]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-15.html]</ref>\n\n16 September 1990 \u2013 [[Peter Beardsley]] scores a hat-trick for Liverpool in their 4\u20130 league win over Manchester United at [[Anfield]].<ref>[http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/history/past-players/peter-beardsley Peter Beardsley \u2013 Liverpool FC]. Liverpoolfc.tv. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n18 September 1990 - Oldham drop points for the first time this season with a 1-1 draw at home to Charlton, who claim their first point of the season in the process.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-18.html]</ref>\n\n22 September 1990 - Liverpool extend their winning start to the season to six games by winning the [[Merseyside derby]] 3-2 at [[Goodison Park]]. Arsenal keep up the pressure and hold onto second place with a 2-0 win at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]. Oldham remain top of the Second Division with a 1-0 win over [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] at [[Ayresome Park]]. [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] draw level with the top three by beating local rivals Oxford 4-2 at the [[Manor Ground (Oxford)|Manor Ground]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-22.html]</ref>\n\n25 September 1990 \u2013 [[Ian Wright]] and [[Mark Bright]] both score hat-tricks for Crystal Palace in their 8\u20130 home win over Southend United in the League Cup second round first leg at [[Selhurst Park]].<ref>[http://www.holmesdale.net/page.php?id=82&story=4702 Top 10 hat-tricks \u2013 Crystal Palace FC Supporters' Website \u2013 The Holmesdale Online]. Holmesdale.net. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n26 September 1990 \u2013 Paul Gascoigne scores four goals for Tottenham in their 5\u20130 win over Hartlepool United (managed by former Tottenham defender [[Cyril Knowles]]) in the League Cup second round first leg at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref>[http://www.topspurs.com/9091.htm the world famous unofficial home of Spurs on the internet]. Topspurs. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n29 September 1990 - Liverpool's 1-0 win over Sunderland at [[Roker Park]] gives them a 100% record after seven games, and they extend their lead to six points after Arsenal are held to a 2-2 draw at Leeds. Tottenham and Crystal Palace are level on points with [[George Graham (footballer)|George Graham]]'s men. Manchester United's title hopes are dented when a [[Stuart Pearce]] goal gives Nottingham Forest a 1-0 win at [[Old Trafford]]. Luton climb to sixth place with a 3-1 win over Norwich at [[Carrow Road]]. Sheffield United and Derby occupy the bottom places, both winless after seven games. Oldham remain top of the Second Division despite being held to a goalless draw at [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-09-29.html]</ref>\n\n30 September 1990 \u2013 Liverpool, with a 100% record after seven games, are First Division leaders by six points at the end of September. The bottom two places are occupied by Sheffield United and Derby County, who have both yet to win a league game this season.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> In the Second Division, Oldham Athletic lead the way with 20 points from their opening eight games. The other two automatic promotion places are occupied by [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] and [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], and the playoff zone is occupied by [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] (in contention for a second successive promotion), [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] and [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]].<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=29&Month=Sep&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1990-09-29). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 October 1990 - [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] go second in the Second Division with a 1-0 win at Port Vale, boosting their hopes of a second successive promotion.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-01.html]</ref>\n\n4 October 1990 \u2013 [[Peter Thomas Taylor|Peter Taylor]], former managerial partner of [[Brian Clough]], dies suddenly of pulmonary fibrosis whilst on holiday in Costa De Los Pinos, Majorca, at the age of 62.\n\n6 October 1990 \u2013 In the biggest Second Division win of the season, [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] beat [[Hull City F.C.|Hull City]] 7\u20131 at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]].<ref>[http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=4&ham=1991&united=2nd_Division_1990-91 2nd Division 1990\u201391]. Westhamstats.info. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]] boost their hopes of a third promotion in four seasons by beating Bristol City 4-0 at home, with [[Steve Bull]] scoring a hat-trick. In the First Division, [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] draw 3-3 in a thrilling match at [[The Dell, Southampton|The Dell]]. Liverpool make it eight wins in a row by beating Derby 2-0 at [[Anfield]], while Arsenal keep the gap between themselves and the leaders at six points by beating Norwich 2-0 at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-06.html]</ref>\n\n7 October 1990 - The pressure mounts on Everton manager [[Colin Harvey]] after a 3-1 defeat at Nottingham Forest leaves his side third from bottom in the First Division after just one win and five points from their opening eight games.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-07.html]</ref>\n\n12 October 1990 \u2013 West Ham United strengthen their promotion bid with a \u00a3600,000 move for [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] defender [[Tim Breacker]].<ref name=\"soccerbase1\">[http://www.soccerbase.com/transfers_by_value.sd?lower_value=&higher_value=100000000&seasonid=120&x=31&y=4  Soccerbase] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n20 October 1990 \u2013 21 of the 22 players on the pitch [[Manchester United F.C.\u2013Arsenal F.C. brawl (1990)|brawl]] in Arsenal's 1\u20130 league win over Manchester United at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/5224475/Manchester-United-v-Arsenal-A-history-of-football-warfare.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Emma |last=Barrow |title=Manchester United v Arsenal: A history of football warfare |date=28 April 2009 |accessdate=30 October 2010  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929043529/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/5224475/Manchester-United-v-Arsenal-A-history-of-football-warfare.html |archivedate=29 September 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In their ninth league game of the season, Liverpool drop points for the first time when Norwich City hold them to a 1\u20131 draw at [[Carrow Road]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> The gap between first and second place is cut to four points as a result. Tottenham keep up the pressure with a 4-0 home win over Sheffield United, with [[Paul Walsh]] scoring a hat-trick. The bottom two clubs are still winless after nine games.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-20.html]</ref>\n\n24 October 1990 - Aston Villa beat Italian favourites [[Inter Milan]] 2-0 at [[Villa Park]] in the [[UEFA Cup]] second round first leg. In the Second Division, Newcastle's promotion hopes are hit by a 3-1 home defeat to struggling Charlton.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-24.html]</ref>\n\n27 October 1990 \u2013 The [[Manchester derby]] at [[Maine Road]] ends in a 3\u20133 draw between City and United.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Liverpool return to their winning ways with a 2-0 home win over Chelsea. Arsenal keep up the pressure with a 1-0 home win over Sunderland at Highbury, as do Tottenham with a 2-1 win at Nottingham Forest, and Crystal Palace with a thrilling 4-3 home win over Wimbledon. The top four in the First Division are all unbeaten after 10 games, as are the Second Division's top two clubs Oldham and West Ham after 14 games, and Fourth Division leaders Torquay after 13 games.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-27.html]</ref>\n\n31 October 1990 \u2013 [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] sack manager [[Colin Harvey]] after their worst start to a league season leaves them third from bottom in the First Division. Below them are Derby County and winless Sheffield United, while Liverpool remain top with nine wins from their opening 10 games. Arsenal, Tottenham Hotspur and Crystal Palace are their nearest contenders, and the top four are all still undefeated in the league.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> The Second Division promotion race is heating up, with Oldham Athletic still top of the table and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] having crept up to second place. Sheffield Wednesday occupy the third and final automatic promotion place. [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] have all climbed into the relegation zone this month. [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic's]] hopes of an immediate return to the First Division appear to be over as they occupy second from bottom place in the Second Division with eight defeats from their opening 13 games.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=27&Month=Oct&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1990-10-27). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref> The [[Football League Cup]] third round action includes a [[Mick Harford]] hat-trick for Derby in a 6-0 home win over his old club Sunderland. Manchester United beat Liverpool 3-1 at [[Old Trafford]]. Nottingham Forest keep their hopes of a third successive League Cup triumph alive with a 2-1 win at [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-10-31.html]</ref>\n\n1 November 1990 \u2013 Spencer Trethewy is dismissed from the Aldershot board of directors just three months after saving the club from closure, after it is revealed that he was unable to pay back the \u00a3200,000 he borrowed to keep the [[Hampshire]] based club afloat.<ref name=\"mirrorfootball.co.uk\"/>\n\n3 November 1990 - Crystal Palace suffer their first league defeat of the season when they lose 2-0 to Manchester United at Old Trafford. Derby beat Luton 2-1 to make it back-to-back victories in a boost to their survival hopes. Managerless Everton beat QPR 3-0 at Goodison Park.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-03.html]</ref>\n\n4 November 1990 - Tottenham's unbeaten league start ends and their title hopes are hit by a major blow when they lose 3-1 at home to Liverpool, who maintain a four-point lead over their nearest challengers Arsenal, while third placed Tottenham are now nine points off the top.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-04.html]</ref>\n\n7 November 1990 \u2013 [[Howard Kendall]] leaves [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] to begin his second spell as Everton manager.<ref>[http://www.evertonfc.com/history/howard-kendall.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6JFad8Drn?url=http://www.evertonfc.com/history/howard-kendall.html |date=30 August 2013 }} Evertonfc.com</ref> 34-year-old midfielder [[Peter Reid]] is put in temporary charge of Manchester City. Aston Villa's UEFA Cup hopes are ended when Inter Milan overturn a 2-0 Villa lead in the UEFA Cup second round second leg and win 3-0 in the [[San Siro]]. Manchester United go through to the quarter-finals of the European Cup Winners' Cup by completing a 5-0 aggregate win over [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-07.html]</ref>\n\n10 November 1990 - Liverpool extend their lead at the top of the First Division to six points with a 4-0 home win over Luton, while Arsenal can only manage a goalless draw with Crystal Palace at [[Selhurst Park]]. Tottenham keep their title hopes alive with a 4-2 home win over Wimbledon. Howard Kendall's return to Everton begins with a goalless draw against Sheffield United at [[Bramall Lane]], which keeps Everton in 17th place and means that their hosts are still bottom of the table and winless after 12 games. Derby hold Manchester United to a goalless draw at the [[Baseball Ground]] but miss the chance to climb out of the relegation zone.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-10.html]</ref>\n\n11 November 1990 - Leeds go fifth in the First Division with a 3-2 away win over Manchester City.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-11.html]</ref>\n\n12 November 1990 \u2013 Arsenal are deducted two points and Manchester United lose one point as punishment for last month's player brawl, which increases Liverpool's lead at the top to eight points.\n\n14 November 1990 - [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], 14th in the First Division and on course for their lowest league finish in five years, sack manager [[John Sillett]] after more than four years in charge. The only major action of the day is a 1-1 draw between England and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] in a Euro 92 qualifier at [[Lansdowne Road]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-14.html]</ref>\n\n15 November 1990 - [[Peter Reid]] is appointed player-manager of Manchester City. [[Terry Butcher]] returns to England after more than four years with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] to become player-manager at Coventry City. 31-year-old Butcher, who was released from his Rangers contract for a fee of \u00a3350,000, is the youngest manager in all four divisions of the English league.\n\n17 November 1990 - The first round of the [[FA Cup]] is contested. [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] and [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] are all eliminated by non-league opposition. In the First Division, Terry Butcher begins his managerial career with a 1-0 defeat at home to Liverpool, while second placed Arsenal beat Southampton 4-0. Sheffield United remain winless and bottom of the table after losing 2-0 to Manchester United at Old Trafford.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-17.html]</ref>\n\n21 November 1990 - Cardiff become the fourth league side to be knocked out of the FA Cup by non-league opposition when they lose their first round replay 1-0 to [[Isthmian League|Vauxhall-Opel League]] side [[Hayes F.C.|Hayes]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-21.html]</ref>\n\n27 November 1990 - Liverpool sign 19-year-old midfielder [[Don Hutchison]] from Fourth Division [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] for \u00a3175,000. Second Division bottom club [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] sack manager [[Colin Lee]] after eight months in charge.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/walsall/1779667.stm]</ref>\n\n28 November 1990 - [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] beat [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 6-2 at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] in a League Cup fourth round tie, in which 19-year-old winger [[Lee Sharpe]] scores a hat-trick. Nottingham Forest's hopes of three League Cup triumphs in a row are ended when they lose 5-4 to Coventry at [[Highfield Road]], with [[Kevin Gallacher]] scoring a hat-trick for the winners and [[Nigel Clough]] scoring a hat-trick for the losers.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-11-28.html]</ref>\n\n29 November 1990 - Manchester United offer a professional contract to trainee winger [[Ryan Giggs]] on his 17th birthday.\n\n30 November 1990 \u2013 Liverpool remain unbeaten and top of the First Division as November draws to a close, four points ahead of an Arsenal side who are also unbeaten. Sheffield United are still looking for their first league win of the season after 14 games, while Derby County have climbed out of the relegation zone at the expense of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> In the Second Division, West Ham United have taken over from Oldham Athletic as Second Division leaders, while Sheffield Wednesday occupy third place. The playoff zone is occupied by Middlesbrough, Wolverhampton Wanderers, Millwall and Notts County. Newly promoted [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] stand just two points outside the playoff zone in 10th place, sparking hopes that manager [[Gerry Francis]] could soon deliver First Division football to the club for the first time ever.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=24&Month=Nov&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1990-11-24). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 December 1990 - Sheffield United are still looking for a league win 15 games into the season, with just four points to their name, after losing 2-1 at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], while Derby's upswing continues and they climb to 14th place with a 2-1 win at Sunderland, who stand 16th. A [[Lee Sharpe]] goal gives Manchester United a 1-0 win at Everton, United's first win at Goodison Park since January 1982. There is thrilling action in the Second Division when a 5-4 win for the hosts at [[Filbert Street]] sees [[David Kelly (association footballer)|David Kelly]] score a hat-trick for [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester]] and [[Micky Quinn]] score a hat-trick for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]]. The result helps lift Leicester clear of the relegation zone, while Newcastle are now 16th in the Second Division and six points adrift of the players, mounting the pressure on manager [[Jim Smith (footballer, born 1940)|Jim Smith]] who had almost delivered Newcastle promotion last season. West Ham remain top of the Second Division with a 3-1 home win over West Bromwich Albion, Port Vale close in on the playoffs with a 5-1 home win over Plymouth, Oldham retain second place with a 6-1 home win over Brighton, and Middlesbrough go third win a 3-0 home win over Hull.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-01.html]</ref>\n\n2 December 1990 \u2013 Arsenal end Liverpool's unbeaten League run by beating them 3\u20130 at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]], cutting the gap at the top to two points.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/>\n\n4 December 1990 \u2013 Luton Town win the [[Soccer Six]] at the [[Manchester Central Convention Complex|G-Mex Centre]], beating Liverpool 4\u20130 in the final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Six of the best from slick Luton|date=5 December 1990|url=http://kjellhanssen.com/1990/12/05/six-of-the-best-from-slick-luton/|accessdate=21 June 2015|work=Daily Express}}</ref>\n\n8 December 1990 - Heavy snow causes many Football League and FA Cup fixtures to be postponed, but a decent amount of matches in the less seriously affected areas go ahead. Arsenal miss the chance to go ahead at the top of the table on goal difference when they are held to a 1-1 draw at Luton. Tottenham draw 3-3 at home to Sunderland. The first match between Manchester United and Leeds United at Old Trafford for nearly a decade ends in a 1-1 draw. Everton increase Coventry's relegation worries and boost their own chances of staying clear of relegation with a 1-0 win at Goodison Park. West Ham remain firmly in the lead at the top of the Second Division with a 1-0 win at struggling Portsmouth.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-08.html]</ref>\n\n13 December 1990 \u2013 [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] pay \u00a31million for a player for the first time in their history by signing midfielder [[Alan McLoughlin]] from [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref name=\"Soccer Base\">[http://www.soccerbase.com/transfers_by_value.sd?lower_value=&higher_value=100000000&seasonid=120&x=31&y=4  Soccer Base] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n15 December 1990 - Liverpool are four points ahead at the top of the First Division, with a game in hand, after beating Sheffield United 2-0 to leave their hosts winless and still with only four points to their name so far this season, while Arsenal are held to a 2-2 draw at home to Wimbledon. A 10-goal thriller at the [[Baseball Ground]] sees Chelsea beat Derby 6-4. QPR remain second from bottom with a 2-1 defeat at home to Nottingham Forest.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-15.html]</ref>\n\n19 December 1990 - [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] captain [[Tony Adams]] is sentenced to four months in prison for drink-driving after being more than three times over the legal alcohol limit when he crashed his car in [[Southend-on-Sea]] seven months ago.\n\n21 December 1990 - Oldham go top of the Second Division on goal difference with a 5-3 home win over Plymouth.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-21.html]</ref>\n\n22 December 1990 \u2013 Sheffield United beat [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] to win their first First Division game of the season at the seventeenth attempt, but remain bottom of the table.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Liverpool remain comfortably in the lead at the top of the table with a 3-2 home win over Southampton. Manchester United win 3-1 at Wimbledon. West Ham miss out on the chance to return to the top of the Second Division with a 1-0 defeat at Barnsley.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-22.html]</ref>\n\n23 December 1990 - The last matches before Christmas are played. Arsenal extend their unbeaten start to the season to 18 games with a goalless draw at Aston Villa, although Liverpool are still six points ahead of them and have a game in hand. QPR miss the chance to climb out of the relegation zone when Derby hold them to a 1-1 draw at the Baseball Ground. Leeds hold on to fifth place with a 1-0 win over Sunderland at [[Roker Park]]. Three players are sent off in a goalless draw between Leicester and Watford at [[Filbert Street]]. In the Third Division, [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] boost their hopes of winning promotion in [[Phil Holder|Phil Holder's]] first season in management by beating [[Wigan Athletic]] 1-0 at [[Griffin Park]]. In the Fourth Division, [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] keep their playoff hopes alive with a 1-0 win over [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], who are now 18th in the table.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-23.html]</ref>\n\n26 December 1990 - The [[Boxing Day]] action in the First Division sees leaders Liverpool held to a 1-1 draw by QPR at [[Loftus Road]], allowing Arsenal to cut their lead to four points (with a game in hand) by beating Derby 3-0 at Highbury. Coventry boost their survival bid with a 2-0 home win over Tottenham. Crystal Palace remain in the hunt for the title with a 2-1 home win over Sunderland. Leeds go fourth with a 4-1 home win over Chelsea. Sheffield United make it back-to-back victories by winning 1-0 at Luton. Manchester United beat Norwich City 3-0 at [[Old Trafford]], ending [[Dave Stringer|Dave Stringer's]] team's run of five victories in their previous clashes between the two sides. West Ham go back to the top of the Second Division with a 2-0 home win over Oldham. Bristol City beat Portsmouth 4-1 to move to the brink of the playoff zone and boost their chances of a second successive promotion, while the bottom two of Hull and Oxford draw 3-3 at [[Boothferry Park]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-26.html]</ref>\n\n29 December 1990 - Arsenal cut Liverpool's lead of the First Division to a single point by beating Sheffield United 4-1 at Highbury, although [[Kenny Dalglish|Kenny Dalglish's]] men still have two games in hand. Leeds go third with a 3-0 home win over Wimbledon. Coventry, Everton, QPR and Southampton all claim victories in their fight to avoid relegation. There is no shortage of excitement in the Second Division, including Oxford climbing five places off the bottom of the table with a 3-1 win over Blackburn at [[Ewood Park]]. Ipswich and Charlton draw 4-4 at [[Portman Road]]. Newcastle's frustrating season continues with a 2-0 home defeat to Notts County, which leaves them rooted in the bottom half of the table.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-29.html]</ref>\n\n30 December 1990 - The last fixture of 1990 sees Liverpool lose 1-0 to Crystal Palace at Selhurst Park, which boosts [[Steve Coppell|Steve Coppell's]] side's hopes of winning their first ever major trophy in the shape of the league title.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1990-12-30.html]</ref>\n\n31 December 1990 \u2013 The year ends with Arsenal, still unbeaten but having had two points deducted, one point behind of Liverpool at the top of the First Division. Crystal Palace and Leeds United occupy third and fourth respectively, while Sheffield United remain bottom of the table and Sunderland have slipped into the bottom two.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> West Ham United stand top of the Second Division, followed in second place by Oldham Athletic and in third place by Sheffield Wednesday. Middlesbrough, Notts County, Wolverhampton Wanderers and Bristol City occupy the playoff zone. Newcastle United, who began the season among the favourites for promotion, occupy a lowly 16th place and are just four points above the relegation zone that threatens them with Third Division football for the first time.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=29&Month=Dec&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1990-12-29). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 January 1991 - The new year begins with [[Paul Gascoigne]] being sent off in Tottenham's 2-1 defeat at home to Manchester United. Everton's resurgence under Howard Kendall continues with a 2-1 win at Chelsea. Sheffield United make it three wins from four games but remain bottom of the table with a 1-0 home win over QPR. The biggest drama in the Second Division comes at [[Fratton Park]], where Portsmouth boost their survival hopes with a 5-1 home win over bottom club Hull City.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-01.html]</ref>\n\n2 January 1991 - Nottingham Forest beat Norwich 6-2 at [[Carrow Road]] in the First Division.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-02.html]</ref>\n\n5 January 1991 - The [[FA Cup]] third round produces a series of thrilling matches, perhaps the most notable being Second Division West Bromwich Albion's 4-2 home defeat to non-league [[Woking F.C.|Woking]]. [[National League|GM Vauxhall Conference]] title hopefuls [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] find themselves on the receiving end of a 5-0 defeat at home to Portsmouth. Chelsea suffer a shock 3-1 defeat at home to Second Division strugglers Oxford. Arsenal beat Sunderland 2-1 at Highbury, while Liverpool are held to a 1-1 draw at Blackburn.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-05.html]</ref>\n\n6 January 1991 - Fourth Division [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] attract more than 20,000 fans to [[Turf Moor]], where they see [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] win the FA Cup third round tie 1-0. [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], hopeful of following their Second Division rivals Leeds into the First Division for the first time, attract a crowd of more than 22,000 to [[Oakwell]] to watch a 1-1 draw. Last season's beaten finalists Crystal Palace draw 0-0 with Nottingham Forest.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-06.html]</ref>\n\n7 January 1991 - Manchester United begin their defence of the FA Cup with a 2-1 home win over QPR.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-07.html]</ref>\n\n8 January 1991 - Liverpool sign winger [[Jimmy Carter (footballer)|Jimmy Carter]] from [[Millwall F.C.|Milwall]] for \u00a3800,000, on the same day that they beat Blackburn 3-0 in the FA Cup third round replay at Anfield to keep their hopes of a unique second double firmly on track.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-08.html]</ref> Brian Talbot is sacked as West Bromwich Albion manager following their shock FA Cup defeat.\n\n9 January 1991 - In front of a smaller crowd than the one which saw them draw 1-1 at Oakwell three days ago, Leeds beat Barnsley 4-0 in the FA Cup third round replay at Elland Road. The other replays see Coventry beat Wigan 1-0 at [[Springfield Park (Wigan)|Springfield Park]] and Wimbledon beat Aston Villa 1-0 at [[Plough Lane]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-09.html]</ref>\n\n10 January 1991 \u2013 34-year-old former England defender [[Viv Anderson]] joins Second Division promotion chasers Sheffield Wednesday on a free transfer from Manchester United.<ref>http://www.soccerbase.com/transfers_by_value.sd?lower_value=&higher_value=100000000&seasonid=120&x=31&y=4| {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n12 January 1991 - Liverpool remain top of the table but drop two points when they are held to a goalless draw at Aston Villa. Arsenal miss the chance to go top when they are held to a goalless draw in the [[North London derby]] at [[White Hart Lane]]. [[Matthew Le Tissier]] and [[Rod Wallace]] score two goals each in Southampton's 4-3 win at Luton. Manchester United remain in the top five with a 3-0 home win over Sunderland.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-12.html]</ref>\n\n13 January 1991 - Everton win 2-0 at Goodison Park in Howard Kendall's first match in charge against his old club Manchester City.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-13.html]</ref>\n\n15 January 1991 - Liverpool sign 17-year-old midfielder [[Jamie Redknapp]] from [[AFC Bournemouth]] for \u00a3350,000.\n\n16 January 1991 - Leeds United beat Aston Villa 4-1 in the FA Cup quarter final, while Southampton take Manchester United to a replay with a 1-1 draw, while the clash between Chelsea and Tottenham also goes to a replay after the first match at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] ends in a goalless draw. In the only league action of the day, Newcastle's woes continue when they lose 4-2 at Brighton in the Second Division, a result which lifts the [[South Coast of England|South Coast]] club into the playoff zone.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-16.html]</ref>\n\n17 January 1991 \u2013 Sheffield United pay a club record \u00a3450,000 for Crystal Palace midfielder [[Glyn Hodges]], who played under Blades manager [[Dave Bassett]] several years ago when he was in charge at Wimbledon.<ref name=\"soccerbase1\"/>\n\n19 January 1991 - Arsenal go top of the First Division for the first time this season with a 1-0 home win over Everton, while Liverpool (who still have a game in hand) can only manage a 1-1 draw at home to Wimbledon. Crystal Palace's title hopes are hit by a 3-1 home defeat to Norwich.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-19.html]</ref>\n\n23 January 1991 - Chelsea go through to the League semi-finals with a 3-0 win their quarter-final replay at Tottenham. [[Mark Hughes]] scores a hat-trick for Manchester United in their 3-2 replay win over Southampton at Old Trafford which takes them to this stage of the competition for the first time in eight seasons, while 20-year-old striker [[Alan Shearer]] scores twice for the losing side. Sheffield Wednesday win 1-0 at Coventry in their delayed quarter-final tie.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-23.html]</ref>\n\n26 January 1991 - The first FA Cup fourth round ties are played. Second Division promotion rivals Millwall and Sheffield Wednesday clash in [[South London]] and battle out a dramatic 4-4 draw. A South Coast clash sees Portsmouth beat [[AFC Bournemouth]] 5-1 at Fratton Park. Manchester United beat [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] 1-0 at Old Trafford. The only First Division action of the day sees Sheffield United beat Derby 1-0 at [[Bramall Lane]] to boost their survival bid.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-26.html]</ref>\n\n27 January 1991 \u2013 Woking's FA Cup dream comes to an end in the fourth round when they lose 1\u20130 to Everton at [[Goodison Park]]. Arsenal and Leeds draw 0-0 in their fourth round clash at Highbury.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-27.html]</ref>\n\n28 January 1991 - Nottingham Forest beat Crystal Palace 3-0 in their second FA Cup third round replay at the [[City Ground]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-01-28.html]</ref>\n\n29 January 1991 \u2013 [[David Pleat]] is sacked after three years as manager of [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], the Second Division strugglers.<ref name=\"soccerbase.com\">[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=351 David Pleat | Latest Betting Odds]. Soccer Base. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627050543/http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=351 |date=27 June 2009 }}</ref> His assistant [[Gordon Lee (footballer)|Gordon Lee]], the former Everton manager, is placed in temporary charge.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=546 Gordon Lee | Latest Betting Odds]. Soccer Base. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n30 January 1991 - [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] sign striker [[David Speedie]] from [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] for \u00a3675,000.\n\n31 January 1991 \u2013 Arsenal are one point ahead of Liverpool, who have a game in hand, at the top of the First Division. Meanwhile, Crystal Palace are still in contention for a first-ever league title, six points off the top, while Sheffield United remain bottom.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> West Ham United, Oldham Athletic and Sheffield Wednesday continue to occupy the top three places in the Second Division. Notts County, Middlesbrough, Brighton and Millwall occupy the playoff zone.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=19&Month=Jan&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1991-01-19). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 February 1991 \u2013 [[Paul Birch (footballer, born 1962)|Paul Birch]] leaves [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] after 10 years to join [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] for \u00a3400,000.<ref name=\"Soccer Base\"/>\n\n2 February 1991 \u2013 Arsenal suffer their first league defeat of the season in their 24th game, going down 2\u20131 to Chelsea at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> They remain top of the league by a single point, although Liverpool have two games in hand. Sheffield United are now just two points adrift of safety after a 4-1 home win over Southampton. In the Second Division, Oldham suffer a shock 5-1 defeat at Oxford.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-02-02.html]</ref>\n\n12 February 1991 \u2013 Aston Villa sign defender [[Neil Cox (footballer)|Neil Cox]] from [[Scunthorpe United]] for \u00a3400,000, a record fee for a Fourth Division player.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[http://www.soccerbase.com/transfers_by_value.sd?lower_value=&higher_value=100000000&seasonid=120&x=31&y=4 Football Betting | Place Your Football Bet Today | Soccer Base] {{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n17 February 1991 - Liverpool and Everton draw 0-0 in an [[Merseyside derby|all Merseyside]] FA Cup fifth round tie at [[Anfield]].\n\n20 February 1991 \u2013 Sheffield Wednesday sign 19-year-old striker [[Gordon Watson (footballer, born 1971)|Gordon Watson]] from [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] for \u00a3250,000. The FA Cup fourth round replay between Liverpool ends in a dramatic 4-4 draw at [[Goodison Park]], forcing a second replay.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n21 February 1991 - In a record fee for a non-league player, [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] striker [[Andy Clarke]] joins [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] for \u00a3250,000.\n\n22 February 1991 \u2013 [[Kenny Dalglish]] announces his resignation as Liverpool manager. Long-serving coach [[Ronnie Moran]] is appointed caretaker manager. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n24 February 1991 - Arsenal return to the top of the First Division on goal difference, beating Crystal Palace 4-0 at Highbury, while Liverpool suffer a shock 3-1 defeat at Luton. Wimbledon go sixth with a 5-1 win over Tottenham at Plough Lane.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-02-23.html]</ref> In the first leg of the League Cup semi finals, Sheffield Wednesday win 2-0 at Chelsea and Manchester United win 1-0 at Leeds.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-02-24.html]</ref>\n\n27 February 1991 - Everton beat Liverpool 1-0 in the second replay of the FA Cup fifth round tie at Goodison Park, ending Liverpool's hopes of a unique second double. Sheffield Wednesday reach their first cup final in 25 years by beating Chelsea 3-1 in the League Cup semi-final second leg.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-02-27.html]</ref>\n\n28 February 1991 \u2013 February draws to a close with Arsenal now ahead of Liverpool at the top of the First Division on goal difference, while Crystal Palace are five points behind. At the other end of the table, a splendid run of form has moved Sheffield United six points clear of bottom-placed Derby County. The Blades are level on goal difference with Coventry City, Sunderland and Queens Park Rangers.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> West Ham United, Oldham Athletic and Sheffield Wednesday continue to lead the way in the Second Division. Middlesbrough, Notts County, Brighton and Millwall occupy the playoff zone, with Bristol City continuing to turn up the heat on them in their bid for a second successive promotion.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=23&Month=Feb&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1991-02-23). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\nMarch - [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] captain [[Alan Hansen]] retires after 14 years at the club, having been out of action for almost a year due to injury.\n\n2 March 1991 - Manchester United give Ryan Giggs his senior debut as a substitute in a league match at Old Trafford, which ends in a 2-0 defeat to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. [[Dean Saunders]] scores a hat-trick for Derby in a 3-3 relegation crunch clash with Sunderland at the Baseball Ground.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-02.html]</ref>\n\n3 March 1991 \u2013 Arsenal move three points clear at the top of the First Division by beating Liverpool 1\u20130 at Anfield thanks to a goal by [[Paul Merson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/SeasonArchive/Game/1778|title=Matchdetails from Liverpool - Arsenal played on Sunday 3 March 1991 - LFChistory - Stats galore for Liverpool FC!|first=|last=LFChistory.net|date=|website=www.lfchistory.net|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n16 March 1991 - Liverpool go back to the top of the First Division by beating Sunderland 2-1 at Anfield.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-16.html]</ref>\n\n17 March 1991 - Arsenal return to the top of the First Division on goal difference (with a game in hand) by beating Leeds 2-0 at Highbury.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-17.html]</ref>\n\n20 March 1991 \u2013 Swindon Town sell defender [[Paul Bodin]] to Crystal Palace for \u00a3550,000.<ref name=\"Soccer Base\"/>\n\n22 March 1991 - [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] sign striker [[Robert Rosario]] from [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] for \u00a3600,000.\n\n23 March 1991 \u2013 Liverpool beat Derby County 7\u20131 at the [[Baseball Ground]], the first time in 28 years that a First Division team has scored seven goals away from home.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Arsenal's goalless draw at Norwich sends Liverpool back to the top of the table.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-23.html]</ref>\n\n26 March 1991 - [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] sign [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet]] winger [[Andrei Kanchelskis]], 22, from [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk]] for \u00a31million. [[Ossie Ardiles]] leaves [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] to become the new manager of [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] following the resignation of [[Jim Smith (footballer, born 1940)|Jim Smith]].\n\n27 March 1991 - In the only league game of the day, Oldham and West Ham remain locked together at the top of the Second Division after a 1-1 draw at [[Boundary Park]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-29.html]</ref>\n\n28 March 1991 \u2013 The 90-day inquest into the [[Hillsborough disaster]] records a verdict of accidental death on the 95 Liverpool fans who died as a result of their injuries at the FA Cup semi-final on 15 April 1989.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/march/28/newsid_2531000/2531015.stm BBC ON THIS DAY | 28 | 1991: Family anger at Hillsborough verdict]. BBC News. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n30 March 1991 \u2013 Manchester United centre-back [[Steve Bruce]] scores twice in a 3\u20130 away league win over his old club Norwich City, becoming the first defender to score ten league goals this season.<ref>[http://www.manchester-united-fans-site.com/manchester-united-results-1990-1991.html Manchester United Results 1990\u20131991, Division One, FA Cup, League Cup, European] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126223849/http://www.manchester-united-fans-site.com/manchester-united-results-1990-1991.html |date=2010-11-26 }}. Manchester-united-fans-site.com. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref> Arsenal return to the top of the First Division by beating Derby 2-0 at the Baseball Ground, while Liverpool suffer a shock 3-1 defeat at home to QPR.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-03-30.html]</ref>\n\n31 March 1991 \u2013 March draws to a close with Arsenal leading Liverpool by two points. Sheffield United's incredible revival has continued as they now stand 12th in the table, but Derby County are twelve points adrift of safety, and Sunderland occupy the other relegation place.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Oldham Athletic and West Ham United lead the Second Division level on 70 points, with Brighton, Middlesbrough, Millwall and Bristol City occupying the playoff zone. [[Ossie Ardiles]] becomes manager of Newcastle United, who are just six points outside the playoff zone with two games in hand.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=29&Month=Mar&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1991-03-29). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n1 April 1991 \u2013 Liverpool's hopes of retaining their league title are damaged by a 1\u20130 away defeat to Southampton.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/>\n\n3 April 1991 - Arsenal are five points ahead at the top of the First Division with seven games remaining after a 5-0 home win over Aston Villa.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-04-03.html]</ref>\n\n6 April 1991 - Arsenal take a step closer to the title by beating Sheffield United 2-0 at [[Bramall Lane]].<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-04-06.html]</ref>\n\n7 April 1991 \u2013 Crystal Palace win the [[Full Members Cup]] after a 4-1 victory over Everton in the Wembley final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/full-members-cup/1990-1991/results/1991-04 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100219151435/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/full-members-cup/1990-1991/results/1991-04 |archivedate=2010-02-19 }}</ref>\n\n13 April 1991 \u2013 Liverpool's title challenge is kept alive with a thrilling 5\u20134 away win over Leeds United, but the Reds are five points behind Arsenal with five games left. Leeds striker [[Lee Chapman]] finds himself in the unusual position of scoring a hat-trick despite being on the losing side.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/><ref>[http://www.liverweb.org.uk/season.asp?season=199091 Liverpool Results 1990\u201391] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218135945/http://www.liverweb.org.uk/season.asp?season=199091 |date=2012-02-18 }}. Liverweb. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n14 April 1991 \u2013 Tottenham Hotspur end Arsenal's hopes of the double and boost their own hopes of an eighth FA Cup triumph with a 3\u20131 win in the first FA Cup semi-final to be played at Wembley. Nottingham Forest win the other semi-final, crushing West Ham United 4\u20130 at [[Villa Park]].\n\n16 April 1991 \u2013 [[Graeme Souness]] is named as Liverpool's new manager, departing from Rangers, where he is succeeded by [[Walter Smith (footballer)|Walter Smith]]. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n20 April 1991 \u2013 Nottingham Forest record the biggest First Division win of the season by beating Chelsea 7\u20130 at the [[City Ground]].<ref>[http://www.statto.com/football/teams/nottingham-forest/1990-1991/results Nottingham Forest 1990\u20131991 : Results. League Results] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051449/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/nottingham-forest/1990-1991/results |date=March 4, 2016 }}</ref> Derby County lose to Manchester City and are relegated.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> West Ham seal promotion back to the First Division two years after relegation by beating Swindon 2-0 at Upton Park, with five games left to play in the Second Division.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-04-20.html]</ref>\n\n21 April 1991 \u2013 Sheffield Wednesday, chasing promotion to the First Division, achieve a 1\u20130 win over Manchester United in the [[1991 Football League Cup Final|League Cup final]] to end a 56-year trophy drought. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n23 April 1991 - [[David White (English footballer)|David White]] scores four goals for Manchester City in a 5-2 away win over Aston Villa. With three games to go, the title race remains open as both Arsenal and Liverpool win and the gap remains three points wide.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-04-23.html]</ref>\n\n27 April 1919 - Oldham Athletic are promoted to the First Division after 68-year exile by beating Ipswich Town 2-1 a to [[Portman Road]].<ref>[https://www.oldhamathletic.co.uk/news/2017/april/on-this-day-april-27-1991/]</ref>\n\n30 April 1991 \u2013 April draws to a close with Arsenal three points ahead of Liverpool with three matches left, while Crystal Palace's title dreams have ended. Sunderland, Luton Town and last season's runners-up Aston Villa still fighting to avoid relegation alongside Derby County.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/>\n\n1 May 1991 \u2013 England beat [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] 1\u20130 in [[Izmir]] in their fourth European Championship qualifying game. {{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n4 May 1991 \u2013 Arsenal edge closer to the title by drawing 0\u20130 with Sunderland, while Liverpool are beaten 4\u20132 by Chelsea.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/>\n\n6 May 1991 \u2013 Liverpool are beaten 2\u20131 by Nottingham Forest, handing the title to Arsenal,<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> who beat Manchester United 3\u20131. [[Alan Smith (footballer born 1962)|Alan Smith]] scores a hat-trick.<ref name=\"arseweb.com\">[http://www.arseweb.com/history/stats/91.html Arsenal appearances 1990/91]. Arseweb.com. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n8 May 1991 - Aston Villa, First Division runners-up last season, confirm their survival with a 2-1 win at home to Norwich City. Sheffield Wednesday seal an immediate return to the First Division with a 3-1 home win over Bristol City.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-05-08.html]</ref>\n\n11 May 1991 \u2013 Sunderland are relegated to the Second Division as they lose to Manchester City and Luton Town beat Derby County 2\u20130. It is the second season running that Luton have survived on the last day of the season with victory over Derby.<ref name=\"smailesleague\"/> Arsenal end their championship campaign with a 6\u20131 demolition of Coventry City at Highbury, with [[Anders Limpar]] scoring a hat-trick.<ref name=\"arseweb.com\"/> The Second Division campaign ended with Oldham Athletic, already promoted to the First Division for the first time since 1923, crowned as champions thanks to an injury-time final-day Neil Redfearn penalty earning them a 3-2 comeback victory over Sheffield Wednesday. West Ham United, last day losers to 4th-place Notts County, had to settle for second. Sheffield Wednesday took the third automatic promotion spot. Hull City's relegation was confirmed 2 weeks ago, while West Bromwich Albion are relegated alongside them to fall into the Third Division for the first time in their history.<ref>[http://www.oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadgen.asp?Day=11&Month=May&ssnno=120&teamno=404 Oldham Athletic FC News \u2013 Latics Mad]. Oldhamathletic-mad.co.uk (1991-05-11). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n13 May 1991 - Gerry Francis resigns after four years as manager of Bristol Rovers, despite having guided the club a mid table finish in the Second Division a year after winning promotion.\n\n15 May 1991 \u2013 Manchester United mark the return to European football by English clubs with a 2\u20131 win over [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the [[1991 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|European Cup Winners' Cup final]] in [[Rotterdam]]. [[Mark Hughes]] scores both goals. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n18 May 1991 \u2013 Tottenham Hotspur win the FA Cup for the eighth time, beating Nottingham Forest 2\u20131 after extra time in the [[1991 FA Cup Final|final]]. [[Paul Gascoigne]] suffers cruciate knee ligament damage, causing his proposed \u00a38.5million move to Lazio to be put on hold.<ref>[http://www.newsint-archive.co.uk/pages/S.asp?pubsel=BOTH&SrchText=Gascoigne+and+Lazio&edn=&DateFromDD=01&DateFromMM=Jul&DateFromYY=1990&page=&SortOrder=Asc&SortOrder=asc&SortOrder=asc&SortOrder=asc&SortSpec=&DateToDD=31&DateToMM=May&ResultListMax=200&Submit1=Search&source=thetimes&DateToYY=1991&byline=&head=&Collection=NI%C2%A7%3D&Caption=&SortField=SDate&SortField=Pub&SortField=EDN&SortField=Page&ST=NS&Site=ALL&ResultCount=20&BackDD=Day&summreqd=yes&QueryText=%28Gascoigne+and+Lazio%29+%3CAND%3E+%28PUB%3DBOTH%29+%3CAND%3E+%28%28SDate%3E%3D7%2F1%2F1990%29+%3CAND%3E+%28SDate%3C%3D5%2F31%2F1991%29%29&BackMM=Month&indexkey=90C42980957987041730&advsrch=0&BackYY=Year&_P=3&ResultMaxDocs=200& The Times and The Sunday Times Archive]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Newsint-archive.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n20 May 1991 - The First Division campaign ends with a 1-1 draw between Manchester United and Tottenham at Old Trafford.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-05-20.html]</ref>\n\n21 May 1991 - [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]] manager [[Don Howe]] is sacked after 18 months in charge at [[Loftus Road]].\n\n28 May 1991 - Jozef Venglos leaves Aston Villa after just one season as manager.\n\n30 May 1991 \u2013 [[Brian Little (footballer)|Brian Little]], whose [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] side have just secured their second successive promotion and won the Fourth Division title, is appointed as Leicester City's new manager.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=252 Brian Little | Latest Betting Odds]. Soccer Base. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001043929/http://www.soccerbase.com/managers2.sd?managerid=252 |date=1 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\n31 May 1991 - [[Ron Atkinson]], the [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] manager, turns down an offer to become the new Aston Villa manager. Torquay United win promotion to the Third Division after nearly 20 years in the Fourth Division, beating Blackpool on penalties after a 2-2 draw in the Wembley playoff final.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-05-31.html]</ref>\n\n1 June 1991 - [[Gerry Francis]], who was captain of QPR during the 1970s, returns to Loftus Road as manager. Jim Smith is appointed manager of [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. Tranmere reach the Second Division for the first time since 1938 by beating Bolton 1-0 in the Third Division playoff final.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-06-01.html]</ref>\n\n2 June 1991 \u2013 Notts County beat [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] 3\u20131 in the Second Division play-off final to seal promotion to the First Division - their second successive promotion.<ref>[http://www.englishfootballleaguetables.co.uk/season/S1990-91/1991-06-02.html]</ref>\n\n6 June 1991 \u2013 David Pleat is appointed Luton Town manager for the second time.<ref name=\"soccerbase.com\"/> Leeds United pay a club record \u00a31.6million for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] striker [[Rod Wallace]].\n\n7 June 1991 - Ron Atkinson becomes the new Aston Villa manager after accepting an improved offer.\n\n18 June 1991 - Veteran striker [[Trevor Francis]] is appointed player-manager of Sheffield Wednesday.\n\n25 June 1991 - [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], now bankrolled by the wealth of local steel baron [[Jack Walker]], pay a club record \u00a3700,000 for [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] midfielder [[Steve Agnew]].\n\n27 June 1991 \u2013 Former Oldham Athletic goalkeeper [[Andy Goram]] becomes Scotland's first \u00a31million goalkeeper after a move from [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] to [[Rangers F.C.|Glasgow Rangers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=2953|title=Andy Goram - Football Stats - No Club - Age 53 - 1981-2006 - Soccer Base|author=|date=|website=www.soccerbase.com|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==National team==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2019}}\n\n==FA Cup==\n{{Main|1990\u201391 FA Cup}}\n[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] beat [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] 2\u20131 after extra time in the [[1991 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]]. The decisive goal was an own goal by Forest defender [[Des Walker]]. Tottenham's triumph was overshadowed by a knee injury to star midfielder [[Paul Gascoigne]] in the opening 15&nbsp;minutes.\n\n==Football League Cup==\n{{Main|1990\u201391 Football League Cup}}\nSheffield Wednesday earned a shock 1\u20130 victory over their manager Ron Atkinson's old club Manchester United in the [[1991 Football League Cup Final|final]] thanks to a goal from [[John Sheridan (footballer)|John Sheridan]].\n\n==Football League==\n{{main|1990\u201391 Football League}}\n\n===First Division===\n[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] won the First Division after losing just one of their league matches all season. [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] finished runners-up. Third place went to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. Newly promoted [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] had a good season back in the First Division as they finished fourth, and also reached the semi-finals of the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]. At the bottom of the table, [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] went down in last place with just five wins all season despite the 17 league goals of [[Wales|Welsh]] striker [[Dean Saunders]], who was then sold to Liverpool. The other relegation place went to [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].\n{{:1990\u201391 Football League First Division|only_totals=y}}\n\n===Second Division===\n[[Joe Royle]]'s [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] side won the Second Division championship ahead of [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], who were promoted as runners-up. Joining them in promotion were League Cup winners Sheffield Wednesday, who finished in third place. [[Neil Warnock]] guided [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] to a second successive victory in the promotion play-offs. [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] were relegated.\n{{:1990\u201391 Football League|only_totals=y|transcludesection=Second Division}}\n\n====Second Division play-offs====\n\n{{ConfPlayoff | RD1=Semifinals<br>1st leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 19; 2nd leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 22, 1991\n| RD2=Final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]<br>June 2, 1991\n| RD1-seed1='''4th'''\n| RD1-team1='''[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]'''\n| RD1-score1-1=1\n| RD1-score1-2=1\n| RD1-score1-A='''2'''\n| RD1-seed2=7th\n| RD1-team2= [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| RD1-score2-1=1\n| RD1-score2-2=0\n| RD1-score2-A=1\n| RD1-seed3=5th\n| RD1-team3= [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n| RD1-score3-1=1\n| RD1-score3-2=1\n| RD1-score3-A=2\n| RD1-seed4='''6th'''\n| RD1-team4='''[[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]'''\n| RD1-score4-1=4\n| RD1-score4-2=2\n| RD1-score4-A='''5'''\n| RD2-seed1='''4th'''\n| RD2-team1='''[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]]'''\n| RD2-score1='''3'''\n| RD2-seed2=6th\n| RD2-team2= [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| RD2-score2= 1\n}}\n\n===Third Division===\nChampions [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]], runners-up [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] and third-placed [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] occupied the automatic promotion places and all achieved second successive promotions. The fourth promotion place went to play-off winners [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]. Going down to the Fourth Division were [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] and [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]].\n{{:1990\u201391 Football League|only_totals=y|transcludesection=Third Division}}\n\n====Third Division play-offs====\nThe semifinals were decided over two legs, and only the aggregates are given in the schemata below. The final consisted of only a single match.<br>The full results can be found at: [[Football League One play-offs#1991|Football League Division Three play-offs 1991]].\n\n{{ConfPlayoff | RD1=Semifinals<br>1st leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 19; 2nd leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 22, 1991\n| RD2=Final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]<br>June 1, 1991\n| RD1-seed1='''4th'''\n| RD1-team1='''[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]'''\n| RD1-score1-1=1\n| RD1-score1-2=1\n| RD1-score1-A='''2'''\n| RD1-seed2=7th\n| RD1-team2=[[Bury F.C.|Bury]]\n| RD1-score2-1=1\n| RD1-score2-2=0\n| RD1-score2-A= 1\n| RD1-seed3='''5th'''\n| RD1-team3='''[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]'''\n| RD1-score3-1=2\n| RD1-score3-2=1\n| RD1-score3-A='''3'''\n| RD1-seed4=6th\n| RD1-team4=[[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| RD1-score4-1=2\n| RD1-score4-2=0\n| RD1-score4-A= 2\n| RD2-seed1=4th\n| RD2-team1=[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| RD2-score1= 0\n| RD2-seed2='''5th'''\n| RD2-team2='''[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]]''' {{aet}}\n| RD2-score2='''1'''\n}}\n\n===Fourth Division===\nBrian Little's [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] won the Fourth Division championship to earn a second successive promotion, while the other four promotion places went to [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]], [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] and [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]. Torquay were the play-off winners, beating [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in a penalty shoot-out in the final. {{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n[[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]] finished bottom of the league, but avoided relegation into the Conference as the Football League increased in size from 92 to 93 teams for 1991-92.\n{{:1990\u201391 Football League|only_totals=y|transcludesection=Fourth Division}}\n\n====Fourth Division play-offs====\n\n{{ConfPlayoff | RD1=Semifinals<br>1st leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 19; 2nd leg&nbsp;\u2013 May 22, 1991\n| RD2=Final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]]<br>May 31, 1991\n| RD1-seed1='''5th'''\n| RD1-team1='''[[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]'''\n| RD1-score1-1=1\n| RD1-score1-2=2\n| RD1-score1-A='''3'''\n| RD1-seed2=8th\n| RD1-team2=[[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]\n| RD1-score2-1=1\n| RD1-score2-2=1\n| RD1-score2-A=2\n| RD1-seed3=6th\n| RD1-team3=[[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]\n| RD1-score3-1=0\n| RD1-score3-2=1\n| RD1-score3-A=1\n| RD1-seed4='''7th'''\n| RD1-team4='''[[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]'''\n| RD1-score4-1=2\n| RD1-score4-2=0\n| RD1-score4-A='''2'''\n| RD2-seed1=5th\n| RD2-team1=[[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]\n| RD2-score1=2 (4)\n| RD2-seed2='''7th'''\n| RD2-team2='''[[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]''' ([[Penalty shootout (association football)|pen.]])\n| RD2-score2='''2 (5)'''\n}}\n\n===Top goalscorers===\n\n'''First Division'''\n* [[Alan Smith (footballer born 1962)|Alan Smith]] ([[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]) \u2013 22 goals<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html English League Leading Goalscorers] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628202228/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html |date=June 28, 2011 }}. Rsssf.com (2010-09-17). Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n'''Second Division'''\n* [[Teddy Sheringham]] ([[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]) \u2013 38 goals\n\n'''Third Division'''\n* [[Brett Angell]] ([[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]])/[[Tony Philliskirk]] ([[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]) \u2013 26 goals\n\n'''Fourth Division'''\n* [[Steve Norris (footballer)|Steve Norris]] ([[Halifax Town F.C.|Halifax Town]]) \u2013 35 goals\n\n==Non-league football==\nThe divisional champions of the major non-League competitions were:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Competition!!Winners\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Football Conference|Football Conference]]\n|[[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Isthmian League|Isthmian League]]\n|[[Redbridge Forest F.C.|Redbridge Forest]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Northern Premier League|Northern Premier League]]\n|[[Witton Albion F.C.|Witton Albion]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Southern Football League|Southern League]]\n|[[Farnborough Town F.C.|Farnborough Town]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 FA Trophy|FA Trophy]]\n|[[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]]\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 FA Vase|FA Vase]]\n|[[Guiseley F.C.|Guiseley]]\n|}\n\n==Retirements==\n* [[Tommy Hutchison]], 43-year-old midfielder with one of the highest appearance records of any player in English football, played his final game for [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] on 12 March 1991 against [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] in the Third Division.<ref>[http://www.swanseacity-mad.co.uk/footydb/loadtmrs.asp?ssnno=120&teamno=508 Fixtures/Results \u2013 Swansea City FC \u2013 Swansea MAD]. Swanseacity-mad.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n* [[Jim Beglin]], 27-year-old [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] and [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] left-back formerly with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], retires after failing to overcome a long-term knee injury.<ref>[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/displayhero_club.asp?HeroID=36421 Jim Beglin \u2013 Liverpool FC \u2013 Football-Heroes.net]. Sporting-heroes.net. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n* [[Alan Hansen]], 35-year-old Liverpool captain and former [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] international, retires after a year out of action with injury.\n* [[Norman Whiteside]], 26-year-old [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] attacking midfielder, formerly of Manchester United, retires due to a knee injury.<ref>[http://www.newsint-archive.co.uk/pages/S.asp?pubsel=BOTH&SrchText=whiteside&DateFromDD=01&DateFromMM=Aug&DateFromYY=1990&DateToDD=31&DateToMM=Jul&DateToYY=1991&ResultListMax=200&head=&byline=&sect=&Caption=&edn=&page=&SortOrder=Asc&SortField=SDate&Submit1=Search&BackDD=Day&BackMM=Month&BackYY=Year&source=thetimes&SortField=Pub&SortOrder=asc&SortField=EDN&SortOrder=asc&SortField=Page&SortOrder=asc&ST=NS&SortSpec=&ResultMaxDocs=200&Site=ALL&Collection=NI&ResultCount=20&summreqd=yes&indexkey=145B6565996913733050&advsrch=0&QueryText=%28whiteside%29+%3CAND%3E+%28PUB%3DBOTH%29+%3CAND%3E+%28%28SDate%3E%3D8%2F1%2F1990%29+%3CAND%3E+%28SDate%3C%3D7%2F31%2F1991%29%29&_P=1 The Times and The Sunday Times Archive]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Newsint-archive.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-03-23.</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n\nJuly 1990 - [[Eric Anderson (English footballer)|Eric Anderson]], 59, played for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] as a forward during the 1950s.\n\n23 July 1990 - [[Dave Deacon]], 61, played 66 league games for [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], many of them under the management of [[Alf Ramsey]], and later played for [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] when they were still a non-league team.\n\n9 August 1990 - [[Joe Mercer]], 76, who won a total of three league titles as a player with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] (1939) and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] (1948 and 1953), and was later manager of [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], as well as an interim spell as manager of the [[England national football team]] in 1974.\n\n15 August 1990 - [[Billy Hume]], 54, spent most of his career in his native [[Scotland]] but made 10 appearances as a forward for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] between 1958 and 1960.\n\n17 August 1990 - [[Ian Handysides]], 27, former [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] and [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]] forward, died of cancer after a two-year battle against the illness.\n\n20 August 1990 -\n\n** - [[Fred Bennett]], 83, played a total of 287 league games at full-back during the interwar years for [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] and [[Chester City F.C.|Chester]].\n** - [[Bill Curry]], 54, played 391 games as a forward between 1953 and 1969 for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], Brighton, Derby County, [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] and [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]].\n\n8 September 1990 - [[David Longhurst]], 25, [[York City F.C.|York City]] striker, died after collapsing during a Fourth Division fixture at home to Lincoln City.\n\n5 October 1990 - [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1928)|Peter Taylor]], 62, most famous for serving as assistant manager to [[Brian Clough]] at [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] between 1965 and 1982. Also had a spell as manager of non-league [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]] before linking up with Clough, and later returned to Derby as manager from 1982 to 1984.\n\n28 November 1990 - [[Ted Catlin]], 79, played more than 200 games at left-back for [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] during the 1930s and picked up an [[FA Cup]] winner's medal in 1935, also winning five caps for England.\n\nDecember 1990 - [[Pat Jones (footballer)|Pat Jones]], 70, played 425 league games for [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] as a full-back between 1946 and 1957.\n\n22 December 1990 - [[Robin Friday]], 38, who was found dead from heart attack in his [[London]] flat, was a striker for [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] during the 1970s.\n\n24 December 1990 - [[Don Dearson]], 76, played 131 league games for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] during a career which was disrupted by the Second World War, before spending the final few seasons of his career with [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]].\n\n25 January 1991 - [[Frank Soo]], 76, played 173 league games at half-back for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] before the Second World War and 71 times for [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] in the early postwar league campaigns. He later managed 12 different British and overseas club sides and had a brief spell in charge of the [[Norway national football team]].\n\nApril 1991 - [[Bobby Baxter (footballer, born 1911)|Bobby Baxter]], 80, played 247 league games for [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] during the 1930s before completing his league career in his native [[Scotland]] with [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] in the immediate postwar era.\n\nMay 1991 - [[Harold Hobbis]], 78, made 248 league appearances for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] as a winger between 1931 and 1948, and scored one goal in two pre-war appearances for the England team.\n\n22 May 1991 - [[Stan Mortensen]], 69, former [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] forward who scored over 200 goals for the club all competitions, winning the [[FA Cup]] in 1953 and also scoring 23 goals in 25 games for the [[England national football team|England team]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{trim|{{suppress categories|{{English football seasons|1990}}}}}}\n{{1990\u201391 in English football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1990-91 in English football}}\n[[Category:1990\u201391 in English football| ]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - fix links -Andy Clarke", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1990%E2%80%9391_in_English_football"}
{"title_page": "Sergio Galindo", "text_new": "{{No footnotes|date=March 2018}}\n\n'''Sergio Galindo''' (September 2, 1926 &ndash; January 3, 1993) was a Mexican [[novelist]] and [[short-story]] writer.  He was born in [[Xalapa|Jalapa]] in the [[Mexican state|state]] of [[Veracruz]], a region of Mexico that figures prominently in much of his writing.  His most widely acclaimed novels are ''El Bordo'' (\u201cThe Precipice\u201d, 1960) and ''Otilia Rauda'' (1986), the latter filmed as ''La Mujer del Pueblo'' in 2001. Galindo studied at the Mexican National Autonomous University ([[UNAM]]) and in Paris.  He was the founder and first director of the [[University of Veracruz]] Press, where he also founded and edited the journal ''La Palabra y el Hombre'' (\u201cThe Word and the Man\u201d).\n\nHe was Director of the ''[[Palacio de Bellas Artes]]'' ([[National Institute of Fine Arts]]) from 1974 to 1976.\n\n==Prizes, Honours and Translations==\nGalindo was awarded the following prizes and honours: Honorary Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]], Polish award for Cultural Merit, [[Order of the Yugoslav Star|Order of the Star of Yugoslavia]], Mariano Azuela Prize, the Bellas Artes Literature Prize, the [[Xavier Villarrutia Prize]] and the [[Jos\u00e9 Fuentes Mares National Prize for Literature]]. He was elected to the [[Mexican Academy of the Language]] in 1975 and to the [[Spanish Royal Academy]] the following year. In 2006, the University of Veracruz and its [http://www.uv.mx/filu/ International University Book Festival] inaugurated an annual prize for first novels by Latin American writers, called the ''Premio Latinoamericano de Primera Novela Sergio Galindo''. His works have been translated into English, French, Polish, German and Italian.\n\n==Novels==\n*''Polvos de arroz'' (translated into English as \u201cRice Powder\u201d), 1958\n*''La justicia de enero'', 1959\n*''El Bordo'' (translated into English as \u201cThe Precipice\u201d), 1960\n*''La comparsa'', 1964\n*''Nudo'', 1970\n*''El hombre de los hongos'', 1976 ([[El hombre de los hongos|filmed]] in 1980)\n*''Los dos \u00e1ngeles'', 1984\n*''Declive'', 1985\n*''Otilia Rauda'' (translated into English as \u201cOtilia\u2019s Body\u201d), 1986 ([https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0314474/?ref_=nm_flmg_wr_1 filmed] in 2001)\n\n==Short story collections==\n*''La m\u00e1quina vac\u00eda'', 1951\n*''\u00a1Oh hermoso mundo!'', 1975\n*''Este laberinto de hombres'', 1979\n*''Cuentos'', 1982\n*''Terciopelo violeta'', 1985\n\n==Other Writing==\n*''Cartas a mi padre'', 2007 (published posthumously)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.uv.mx/filu/ International University Book Festival] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.uv.mx/lapalabrayelhombre/9/index.html La Palabra y el Hombre] {{in lang|es}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110708045910/http://lapalabrayelhombre.blogspot.com/ La Palabra y el Hombre blog] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.uv.mx/editorial/ Veracruz University Press] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Galindo, Sergio}}\n[[Category:Mexican male novelists]]\n[[Category:Mexican male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Mexican short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Veracruz]]\n[[Category:Members of the Mexican Academy of Language]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:Honorary Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{No footnotes|date=March 2018}}\n\n'''Sergio Galindo''' (September 2, 1926 &ndash; January 3, 1993) was a Mexican [[novelist]] and [[short-story]] writer.  He was born in [[Xalapa|Jalapa]] in the [[Mexican state|state]] of [[Veracruz]], a region of Mexico that figures prominently in much of his writing.  His most widely acclaimed novels are ''El Bordo'' (\u201cThe Precipice\u201d, 1960) and ''Otilia Rauda'' (1986), the latter filmed as ''La Mujer del Pueblo'' in 2001. Galindo studied at the Mexican National Autonomous University ([[UNAM]]) and in Paris.  He was the founder and first director of the [[University of Veracruz]] Press, where he also founded and edited the journal ''La Palabra y el Hombre'' (\u201cThe Word and the Man\u201d).\n\nHe was Director of the ''[[Palacio de Bellas Artes]]'' ([[National Institute of Fine Arts]]) from 1974 to 1976.\n\n==Prizes, Honours and Translations==\nGalindo was awarded the following prizes and honours: Honorary Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]], Polish award for Cultural Merit, [[Order of the Yugoslav Star|Order of the Star of Yugoslavia]], Mariano Azuela Prize, the Bellas Artes Literature Prize, the [[Xavier Villarrutia Prize]] and the [[Jos\u00e9 Fuentes Mares National Prize for Literature]]. He was elected to the [[Mexican Academy of the Language]] in 1975 and to the [[Spanish Royal Academy]] the following year. In 2006, the University of Veracruz and its [http://www.uv.mx/filu/ International University Book Festival] inaugurated an annual prize for first novels by Latin American writers, called the ''Premio Latinoamericano de Primera Novela Sergio Galindo''. His works have been translated into English, French, Polish, German and Italian.\n\n==Novels==\n*''Polvos de arroz'' (translated into English as \u201cRice Powder\u201d), 1958\n*''La justicia de enero'', 1959\n*''El Bordo'' (translated into English as \u201cThe Precipice\u201d), 1960\n*''La comparsa'', 1964\n*''Nudo'', 1970\n*''El hombre de los hongos'', 1976 ([[El hombre de los hongos|filmed]] in 1980)\n*''Los dos \u00e1ngeles'', 1984\n*''Declive'', 1985\n*''Otilia Rauda'' (translated into English as \u201cOtilia\u2019s Body\u201d), 1986 ([https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0314474/?ref_=nm_flmg_wr_1 filmed] in 2001)\n\n==Short story collections==\n*''La m\u00e1quina vac\u00eda'', 1951\n*''\u00a1Oh hermoso mundo!'', 1975\n*''Este laberinto de hombres'', 1979\n*''Cuentos'', 1982\n*''Terciopelo violeta'', 1985\n\n==Other Writing==\n*''Cartas a mi padre'', 2007 (published posthumously)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.uv.mx/filu/ International University Book Festival] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.uv.mx/lapalabrayelhombre/9/index.html La Palabra y el Hombre] {{in lang|es}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110708045910/http://lapalabrayelhombre.blogspot.com/ La Palabra y el Hombre blog] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.uv.mx/editorial/ Veracruz University Press] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Galindo, Sergio}}\n[[Category:Mexican male novelists]]\n[[Category:Mexican male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Mexican short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Veracruz]]\n[[Category:Members of the Mexican Academy of Language]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n", "name_user": "Cjholula", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added MBE category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergio_Galindo"}
{"title_page": "1990\u201391 Wimbledon F.C. season", "text_new": "{{Infobox Football club season\n|club=[[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]\n|season=1990\u201391\n|manager=[[Ray Harford]]\n|chairman=[[Sam Hammam]]\n|stadium=[[Plough Lane]]\n|league=[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|league result=[[1990\u201391 Football League#First Division|8th]]\n|cup1=[[FA Cup]]\n|cup1 result=[[1990\u201391 FA Cup#Fourth round proper|Fourth round]]\n|cup2=[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n|cup2 result=[[1990\u201391 Football League Cup|Second round]]\n|cup3=[[Full Members Cup]]\n|cup3 result=[[1990\u201391 Full Members Cup|Second round]] <br> (Southern Area)\n|league topscorer=[[John Fashanu|Fashanu]] (20)\n|season topscorer=\n|highest attendance=<span class=\"nowrap\">13,733 vs [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]</span> <br> <small>(25 Aug 1990, [[Football League First Division|First Division]])</small>\n|lowest attendance=<span class=\"nowrap\">1,787 vs [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]</span> <br> <small>(12 Dec 1990, [[Full Members Cup]])</small>\n|average attendance=7,631\n|pattern_b1=|leftarm1=0000ff|body1=0000ff|rightarm1=0000ff|shorts1=0000ff|socks1=0000ff|\n|prevseason=[[1989\u201390 Wimbledon F.C. season|1989\u201390]]\n|nextseason=[[1991\u201392 Wimbledon F.C. season|1991\u201392]]\n}}\nDuring the 1990\u201391 English football season, [[Wimbledon F.C.]] competed in the [[Football League First Division]].\n\n==Season summary==\nIn the 1990-91 season under Harford's first full campaign in charge, [[Warren Barton]] was purchased for \u00a3300,000 whilst in the league, Wimbledon had another strong season, finishing in 7th place.\n\nNothing came of the plans for a new ground and at the end of the season, Wimbledon's board decided that [[Plough Lane]] was beyond redevelopment to meet the new [[The Football Association|FA]] rule requiring all-seater stadiums.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/318497.stm|title=A hard lesson to learn|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=1999-04-15|accessdate=2009-06-04}}</ref> Consequently, the club moved to [[Selhurst Park]] before the start of next season, [[groundshare|ground-sharing]] with [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].\n\n==Final league table==\n{{main|1990\u201391 Football League}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=20|Pos\n!width=175|Team\n!width=20|Pld\n!width=20|\n!width=20|W\n!width=20|D\n!width=20|L\n!width=20|F\n!width=20|A\n!width=20|\n!width=20|W\n!width=20|D\n!width=20|L\n!width=20|F\n!width=20|A\n!width=20|\n!width=20|F\n!width=20|A\n!width=30|GD\n!width=20|\n!width=20|Pts\n|-bgcolor=#FFFF00\n|1||align=left| [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] ||38||||15||4||0||51||10||||9||9||1||23||8||||74||18||align=right|+56||||83\n|- style=\"background:#D8BFD8;\"\n|2||align=left| [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] ||38||||14||3||2||42||13||||9||4||6||35||27||||77||40||align=right|+37||||76\n|-\n|3||align=left| [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] ||38||||11||6||2||26||17||||9||3||7||24||24||||50||41||align=right|+9||||69\n|-\n|4||align=left| [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] ||38||||12||2||5||46||23||||7||5||7||19||24||||65||47||align=right|+18||||64\n|-\n|5||align=left| [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] ||38||||12||3||4||35||25||||5||8||6||29||28||||64||53||align=right|+11||||62\n|- style=\"background:#bbccff;\"\n|6||align=left| [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] ||38||||11||4||4||34||17||||5||8||6||24||28||||58||45||align=right|+13||||59\n|-\n|'''7'''||align=left| '''[[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]''' ||'''38'''||||'''8'''||'''6'''||'''5'''||'''28'''||'''22'''||||'''6'''||'''8'''||'''5'''||'''25'''||'''24'''||||'''53'''||'''46'''||align=right|'''+7'''||||'''56'''\n|-\n|8||align=left| [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] ||38||||11||4||4||42||21||||3||8||8||23||29||||65||50||align=right|+15||||54\n|-\n|9||align=left| [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] ||38||||9||5||5||26||15||||4||7||8||24||31||||50||46||align=right|+4||||51\n|- style=\"background:#bbccff;\"\n|10