nder-21 football team|U-21]] and [[Republic of Ireland national football B team|B]] level.</ref>}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|nat=NOR|pos=MF|name=[[\u00d8yvind Leonhardsen]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Robbie Earle]]<ref group=notes>Earle was born in [[Newcastle-under-Lyme]], [[England]], and was called up for England without playing, but also qualified to represent [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] internationally and would make his international debut for Jamaica in 1997.</ref>}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|nat=NGA|pos=FW|name=[[Efan Ekoku]]<ref group=notes>Ekoku was born in [[Cheetham, Manchester|Cheetham]], [[England]], but also qualified to represent [[Nigeria]] internationally and made his international debut for [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in 1994.</ref>}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Dean Holdsworth]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Marcus Gayle]]<ref group=notes>Gayle was born in [[London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham|Hammersmith]], [[London]], and represented them at [[England national under-18 football team|U-18]] level, but also qualified to represent [[Jamaica]] internationally through his father and would make his international debut for [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] in 1998.</ref>}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Gary Elkins (footballer)|Gary Elkins]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=[[Paul Heald]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Jon Goodman]]<ref group=notes>Goodman was born in [[London Borough of Waltham Forest|Waltham Forest]], [[England]], but also qualified to represent the [[Republic of Ireland]] internationally and would make his debut for the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] in 1997.</ref>}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Alan Reeves (footballer)|Alan Reeves]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Andy Thorn (footballer)|Andy Thorn]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=[[Brian McAllister]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Neal Ardley]]}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Stewart Castledine]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Mick Harford]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Chris Perry (English footballer)|Chris Perry]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Andy Clarke (footballer)|Andy Clarke]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=[[Neil Sullivan]]<ref group=notes>Sullivan was born in [[London Borough of Sutton|Sutton]], [[England]], but also qualified to represent [[Scotland]] internationally and made his international debut for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in 1997.</ref>}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Peter Fear]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Gary Blissett]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=26|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Aidan Newhouse]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=27|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=Grant Payne}}\n{{Fs player|no=28|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Steve Talboys]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=29|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Gerald Dobbs]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Roger Joseph]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=31|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=Mark Thomas}}\n{{Fs player|no=32|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Justin Skinner (footballer, born 1972)|Justin Skinner]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=33|nat=IRL|pos=GK|name=[[Brendan Murphy (Meath footballer)|Brendan Murphy]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=34|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Jason Euell]]<ref group=notes>Euell was born in [[London Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]], [[England]], and represented them at [[England national under-21 football team|U-21]] level, but also qualified to represent [[Jamaica]] internationally through his father and would make his international debut for [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] in November 2004.</ref>}}\n{{Fs player|no=35|nat=ENG|pos=DF|name=[[Andy Pearce]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Left club during the season===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=35|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=[[Simon Tracey]]|other=on loan from [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Transfers==\n\n===In===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Pos\n!Name\n!From\n!Fee\n|-\n|25 July 1995\n|GK\n|[[Paul Heald]]\n|[[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]]\n|\u00a3125,000\n|}\n\n===Out===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Pos\n!Name\n!From\n!Fee\n|-\n|5 June 1995\n|DF\n|[[Warren Barton]]\n|[[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n|\u00a34,000,000\n|-\n|8 August 1995\n|FW\n|[[Steve Anthrobus]]\n|[[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]]\n|\u00a325,000\n|}\n\n:Transfers in: {{loss}} \u00a3125,000\n:Transfers out: {{gain}} \u00a34,025,000\n:Total spending: {{gain}} \u00a33,900,000\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n{{Wimbledon F.C. seasons}}\n{{1995\u201396 in English football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1995-96 Wimbledon F.C. season}}\n[[Category:Wimbledon F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:1995\u201396 FA Premier League by team|Wimbledon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n|club=[[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]\n|season=1995\u201396\n|manager=[[Joe Kinnear]]\n|chairman=[[Sam Hammam]]\n|stadium=[[Selhurst Park]]\n|league=[[FA Premier League|Premiership]]\n|league result=[[1995\u201396 FA Premier League|14th]]\n|cup1=[[FA Cup]]\n|cup1 result=[[1995\u201396 FA Cup#Sixth round proper|Quarter finals]]\n|cup2=[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n|cup2 result=[[1995\u201396 Football League Cup#Second round|Second round]]\n|cup3=[[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]\n|cup3 result=[[1995 UEFA Intertoto Cup#Group 10|Group stage]]\n|league topscorer=[[Robbie Earle|Earle]] (11)\n|season topscorer=[[Efan Ekoku|Ekoku]]/[[Dean Holdsworth|Holdsworth]] (16)\n|highest attendance=<span class=\"nowrap\">25,380 vs [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]</span> <br> <small>(3 Feb 1996, [[Premier League]])</small>\n|lowest attendance=<span class=\"nowrap\">3,717 vs [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]</span> <br> <small>(19 Sep 1995, [[Football League Cup|League Cup]])</small>\n|average attendance=13,246\n| pattern_la1 = _navyborder\n| pattern_b1  = _Roma1\n| pattern_ra1 = _navyborder\n| pattern_sh1 = _yellow_stripes\n| pattern_so1 = _yellowline\n| leftarm1    = 000080\n| body1       = 000080\n| rightarm1   = 000080\n| shorts1     = 000080\n| socks1      = 000080\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = _collarred 2\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = _red stripes\n| pattern_so2 = _blackline\n| leftarm2    = E41B17\n| body2       = E41B17\n| rightarm2   = E41B17\n| shorts2     = 000000\n| socks2      = E41B17\n|prevseason=[[1994\u201395 Wimbledon F.C. season|1994\u201395]]\n|nextseason=[[1996\u201397 Wimbledon F.C. season|1996\u201397]]\n}}\nDuring the '''1995\u201396''' English football season, [[Wimbledon F.C.]] competed in the [[FA Premier League]] (known as the FA Carling Premiership for sponsorship reasons). It was their tenth successive season in the top flight of English football and although they finished 14th, lower than on any of the previous nine occasions, they finished high enough to maintain their top flight membership.\n\n==Season summary==\nWith the Premiership's lowest crowds and transfer budget, Wimbledon had begun most of their top division seasons since promotion in 1986 as pre-season relegation favourites, but the \"[[Crazy Gang (football)|Crazy Gang]]\" spirit kept Wimbledon going once again, although their 14th-place finish was their lowest since joining the top flight 10 seasons earlier.\n\n[[Dean Holdsworth]] and [[Efan Ekoku]] were once again a formidable strikerforce, while [[Vinnie Jones]] was as combative as ever and [[Oyvind Leonhardsen]]'s performances attracted attention from several bigger clubs. Manager [[Joe Kinnear]] managed to hold on to all his key assets, as well as adding a few more, over the close season as he grew ever more determined to defy the odds once again. \n\nIt was the last season at Wimbledon for long-serving goalkeeper [[Hans Segers]], who lost his place early in the season to [[Paul Heald]] and was transferred to [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]] soon afterwards. Within a few months however, Kinnear had decided on [[Neil Sullivan]] as his regular goalkeeper. \n\nThe season saw Wimbledon play in European competition for the first (and the only) time in their history, in the Intertoto Cup. However, as [[Selhurst Park]] was unavailable the club were forced to play the matches at [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]'s [[Goldstone Ground]]. The lack of home support affected Wimbledon's performances, and they finished fourth in their group of five after a 4-0 home defeat to [[Turkey|Turkish]] club [[Bursaspor]], a 1-1 draw at [[Slovakia]]n side [[MFK Ko\u0161ice|Ko\u0161ice]], a 0-0 draw with [[Israel]]is [[Beitar Jerusalem F.C.|Beitar Jerusalem]] at home and a 3-0 away defeat at [[Belgium|Belgian]] team [[R. Charleroi S.C.|Charleroi]].\n\n==Kit==\n[[Core (company)|Core]] became Wimbledon's kit manufacturers for the season. [[Birmingham]]-based electronics company [[Elonex]] remained the kit sponsors.<ref>http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Wimbledon/Wimbledon.htm</ref>\n\n==Final league table==\n{{main|1995\u201396 FA Premier League}}\n{{:1995\u201396 FA Premier League|showteam=WDN}}\n\n;Results summary\n{{Fb_rs|hw=5|hd=6|hl=8|hgf=27|hga=33|aw=5|ad=5|al=9|agf=28|aga=37}}\n{{Fb_rs_footer|s=[http://www.statto.com/football/teams/wimbledon/1995-1996/table Statto]|date=September 2015}}\n\n;Results by round\n{{#invoke:sports rbr table|table|legendpos=b\n|header=Round\n|label1= Ground\n| res1=H/A/A/H/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/A/H/A/H/H/A/A/H/A/H/H/A/H/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/A/H/A\n|label2= Result\n| res2=W/W/L/D/W/L/L/L/L/L/L/L/D/L/D/D/D/L/D/W/W/L/L/W/L/L/D/D/D/L/W/W/D/W/W/L/L/D\n|label3= Position\n| res3=4/2/3/6/3/6/9/11/12/14/15/17/16/17/16/17/17/18/18/16/15/15/15/14/16/16/16/15/15/17/15/15/15/15/14/14/14/14\n<!-- -->\n|text_H=Home|text_A=Away\n|color_W=green2|text_W=Win\n|color_D=yellow2|text_D=Draw\n|color_L=red2|text_L=Loss\n|color_1=1st|color_2=2nd|color_3=3rd|color_18-=red1\n\n|source=[http://www.statto.com/football/teams/wimbledon/1995-1996/results Statto.com]\n|date=September 2015\n}}\n\n==Results==\n''Wimbledon's score comes first''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/wimbledon/1995-1996/results |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923060014/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/wimbledon/1995-1996/results |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Legend===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|style=\"background-color: #d0ffe3;\"|<small>Win</small>\n|style=\"background-color: #ffffdd;\"|<small>Draw</small>\n|style=\"background-color: #ffd0e3;\"|<small>Loss</small>\n|}\n\n===FA Premier League===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:100%; text-align:center\"\n!Date!!Opponent!!Venue!!Result!!Attendance!!Scorers\n|-style=\"background-color: #d0ffe3;\"\n| 19 August 1995 ||[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]||H||3-2||9,317||[[Efan Ekoku|Ekoku]], [[Robbie Earle|Earle]], [[Dean Holdsworth|Holdsworth]]\n|-style=\"background-color: #d0ffe3;\"\n| 23 August 1995 ||[[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]||A||3-0||11,837||[[\u00d8yvind Leonhardsen|Leonhardsen]], Holdsworth, [[Jon Goodman|Goodman]]\n|-style=\"background-color: #ffd0e3;\"\n| 26 August 1995 ||[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]||A||1-3||32,226||Earle\n|-style=\"background-color: #ffffdd;\"\n| 30 August 1995 ||[[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]||H||2-2||6,352||Goodman, Holdsworth (pen)\n|-style=\"background-color: #d0ffe3;\"\n| 9 September 1995 ||[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]||H||1-0||19,530||[[Mick Harford|Harford]]\n|-style=\"background-color: #ffd0e3;\"\n| 16 September 1995 ||[[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]||A||0-2||26,928||\n|-style=\"background-color: #ffd0e3;\"\n| 23 September 1995 ||[[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]||H||2-4||13,307||Holdsworth, [[Alan Reeves (footballer)|Reeves]]\n|-style=\"background-color: #ffd0e3;